{[%evp 0,29,32,19,36,40,60,52,47,28,39,27,17,8,12,-7,-11,-10,-16,-4,28,29,24,7,5,11,14,14,15,14,12,3]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Bd3 {The main alternative to 5.Nc3. Let us also have a look at the other ways to defend the central pawn:} ({An early queen sally like} 5. Qd3 {has lately become a frequent guest in the Taimanov and also against Scheveningen structure, so it cannot be underestimated.} d5 (5... Nc6 {is also possible, when} 6. Nc3 {transposes to the 3rd Chapter.}) 6. exd5 {is therefore White's best -} ({dubious is} 6. e5 $6 Nfd7 7. f4 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Re5,Rf4][%cal Gg7g5] , as, besides 8....Nxd4 9.Qxd4 Bc5, White should be aware about the 8....Ndxe5 shot and even 8...g5!?}) (6. Nc3 {can be effectively met by} e5 $1 7. Nf3 Bb4 $1 8. Bg5 (8. exd5 O-O $15) 8... d4 9. O-O-O Nc6 {Black has gained space and should not be worried by an appearance of a knight on the d5-square after} 10. Bxf6 (10. Nd5 $143 Be7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 $15 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ge8g8]}) 10... Qxf6 11. Nd5 Qd6 12. Kb1 O-O $15) 6... Nxd5 {and now:} 7. Be2 (7. Qg3 {is the logical follow-up of Qd1-d3 in many open Sicilians, here it is hindering the smooth development of Bf8, so it makes sense to mobilize the queenside by} Bd7 {[%cal Gb8c6]} ({Black seems to be in order after} 7... h5 $5 8. h4 Qd6 {as well, for example} 9. Qxd6 Bxd6 10. Nb5 Be5 11. Nd2 Bd7 12. Nf3 Bf6 $11) 8. Nb5 ({harmless is} 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Nc6 $11) 8... a6 $5 9. Nd6+ Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qh4 {[%cal Gh4e4]} 11. Nc3 (11. c4 $6 Qe4+) 11... Nb4 $5 $132 ({we are still going to see more of this challenging jump, an alternative is} 11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Qe4+ 13. Be3 Qxc2 14. Rc1 Qe4 $13) 12. Bd3 (12. Qd2 {is an attempt to keep the pair of bishops, but White's lag in development is visible, e.g.} O-O 13. a3 Nd5 $11) 12... Nxd3+ ({just as in reply to 12.Qd2,} 12... Bc6 {deserves serious attention}) 13. Qxd3 (13. cxd3 Qe7) 13... O-O $11) ({As we are going to see, the small prophilaxis} 7. a3 {is not without a reason.} Be7 ({aiming at castling before any new action in the center; Black can also consider} 7... Nd7) (7... Bc5) 8. c4 (8. Nc3 O-O $11) 8... Nf6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be2 (10. Be3 {can be answered with} b6 $5) 10... e5 {Yet another surprising, though justified reaction -} 11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. Qxf5 Nc6 $11 {with firm control over the central squares}) (7. Nc3 $6 {looks quite natural, but, unlike the cautious 7.a3, it is presenting Black with a promising opportunity to fight for the opening advantage by means of the concrete} Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gd8d4] Nd4 is hanging, so the choice is limited to} 8. Qb5+ N8c6 {, when} 9. Be3 {is insufficient to save the c2-pawn because of the temporary pawn sacrifice} e5 $1 10. Nxc6 $140 Nxc2+ 11. Ke2 bxc6 {, forcing} 12. Qxe5+ Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Bxe7 {and, due to the pair of bishops, Black has excellent prospects after} 14. Rd1 Nxe3 15. Kxe3 Be6 $15 {[%csl Re3]}) 7... Bc5 $5 ({an active possibility; interesting, but probably slightly premature is} 7... e5 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O $14) ({less pretending, but solid is} 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O $11) 8. O-O (8. Nb3 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 (9. c3 Bd6 $11) 9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 (10. N1xd2 O-O) 10... Qf6 $5 11. Qd4 $1 {White has to look for trading the queens himself, for 11....Nf4 would be rather unpleasant to meet.} Nc6 12. Qxf6 Nxf6 $11) 8... O-O 9. Rd1 Qf6 $5 10. Nc3 Bxd4 (10... Nc6 $5 11. Nxc6 (11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Be3 Re8 13. c3 Bd7 $11) 11... Nxc3 ({Can} 11... Qxf2+ $6 {be wrong? However, let us prolong the variation after} 12. Kh1 {and we will come upon the exquisite tactics} Nxc3 13. Qxc3 $1 Qxe2 14. Bh6 $3 {(a reminiscence of Jobava - Ponomariov!)} e5 (14... gxh6 15. Rd3 $1 $40 {is the point!}) 15. Nxe5 gxh6 16. Qxc5 {and, even though Black would be able to hold after} Bf5 {, the game is continuing on two results}) 12. Qxc3 Qxc3 13. bxc3 bxc6 {is, therefore, Blsck's safer choice; he has little to complain about even without the c6-pawn, for instance} 14. Bf3 Ba6 15. Bxc6 (15. Bf4 Rac8 $11) 15... Rad8 16. Bf4 Bb6 $11) 11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. Rxd4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nc6 14. Rd6 Rd8 15. Rxd8+ Nxd8 {has simplified to an approximately balanced endgame:} 16. Bg5 (16. f4 Bd7 17. Be3 (17. a4 Rc8 {will immediately remind to White about his wrecked queenside structure}) 17... Ba4 18. Rd1 b6 19. Kf2 Kf8 $11) 16... f6 17. Rd1 Nc6 18. Be3 e5 19. Bc4+ Kf8 20. f3 Ke8 21. g4 b6 {Here, too, Black has neutralized the possible penetration on the 7th rank by centralizing his king, and the restricted Bc8 is able to find a different destination.} 22. Bd3 {can annihilate the queenside after} Be6 23. Bxh7 Bxa2 $11) (5. Nd2 {looks modest, but Black has to reckon with e4-e5:} d6 {is good enough:} ({the straightforward reply} 5... e5 {does not entirely solve the opening problems after the principled} 6. Nb5 $1 a6 7. Nc3 d5 (7... Bb4 8. Nd5 {can lead to a good version of the trendy 7.Nd5 Sveshnikov after} Nxd5 9. exd5 O-O 10. c3 Be7 11. a4 d6 12. Be2 $14) 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nde4 Be6 10. Ng5 $1 Nxc3 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nxe6+ fxe6 13. bxc3 Nd7 14. Bc4 $14) (5... Nc6 $6 {does not stop White's main idea -} 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 Nd5 8. c4 $1 Ne7 9. b3 $14) (5... d5 {is an option, it is transposing to a reliable branch of 3.Nd2 French}) 6. Bd3 {, as in the leading text, brings the bishop to a more active location:} (6. Bb5+ Nbd7 7. O-O a6 8. Be2 (8. Bd3 Nc5 $11) 8... Nc5 9. f3 e5 $5 ({more consistent and energetic than} 9... Be7 10. c4 O-O $11) 10. N4b3 d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nc4 Be6 $1 {(a promising pawn sacrifice)} 13. Nxe5 Qc7 $44) (6. c4 {Now and then, a Maroczy bind with Nd2 instead of on its usual c3-square is definitely not White's dream.} g6 $5 {(an adequate reaction)} 7. b3 Bg7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 $11) (6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O {is an unusual Scheveningen because of the same Nd2:} 8. c4 (8. Re1 Nc6 (8... a6) 9. Nxc6 bxc6 $11) (8. b3 e5 9. Nb5 a6 {with good control over the key d5-height and therefore a fine version of 6.Be2 Classical Sicilian after} 10. Nc3 Be6 $11) 8... Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. b3 a5 11. Bb2 Qc7 12. Qc2 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd7c5] and the knight will try to find in the long run a road to the vulnerable d4-square}) 6... Nbd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7c5]} (6... Nc6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 {allows the fresh try} 8. e5 $5 (8. O-O Be7 {may just transpose}) 8... dxe5 9. O-O (9. Qe2 {must be the same}) 9... Be7 10. Qe2 $14) (6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] is similar in ideas with 6.Be2 from above}) 7. c4 (7. O-O Nc5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qe2 Be7 11. c4 {Reaching the bind without the light-squared bishops is a little achievement for White, though the play remains about equal after} a6 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 Rfe8 $11 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) (7. c3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 a6 $11 {[%cal Gd8c7]}) 7... g6 $5 ({this plan is once again more ambitious than} 7... Be7) 8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1 (9. b3 b6 10. Bb2 Bb7 11. Re1 O-O $11) 9... O-O 10. Bf1 b6 11. Nb1 ({a clear recognition of how shaky this set-up with Nd2 is, but a demanding push like} 11. b4 {can backfire after} a5 12. bxa5 Ng4 $1 {e.g.} 13. Qxg4 Bxd4 14. Rb1 Nc5 $132) 11... Bb7 12. Nc3 a6 $11) 5... Nc6 $1 {A proper moment to question Nd4.} (5... e5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. a3 $14) (5... d6 {, with the queenside knight still on its initial b1-square, is less recommendable in the view of} 6. c4 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3] with the Maroczy bind.}) 6. Nxc6 {Relatively best, as otherwise Black has a free hand in the center:} (6. Nb3 d5 ({both} 6... Bb4+ $5 7. Nc3 O-O 8. O-O Ne5 $11) ({and} 6... Be7 $5 7. O-O O-O {d5 are plausible alternatives}) 7. exd5 Nxd5 $5 ({or} 7... exd5 8. O-O Bd6 9. Re1+ Be6 10. h3 O-O $11) 8. O-O ({the preliminary} 8. Bd2 {can prevent Black's next aggressive option}) 8... Ndb4 $5 9. Be4 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 f5 11. a3 fxe4 12. axb4 Nxb4 13. Be3 (13. Na3 $6 Bd7 {leaves White in search for compensation}) 13... Nxc2 14. Rxa7 Nxe3 (14... Rxa7 15. Bxa7 Nb4 $11) 15. Rxa8 Nxd1 16. Rxc8+ Kd7 17. Ra8 e3 18. fxe3 g6 (18... Nxe3 $144 19. Nc5+ Ke7 20. Nxb7 g6 $11) 19. Nc5+ Ke7 20. Rb8 Nxe3 $11) (6. Nf3 Bc5 $5 ({Black can also choose from} 6... g6 $5 7. O-O Bg7) (6... d5 7. exd5 exd5 8. O-O Bd6 9. Re1+ Be6 10. h3 O-O $11) ({and} 6... Be7 7. O-O d5) 7. O-O d6 8. a3 O-O 9. h3 ({tempting, but also obliging is} 9. b4 Bb6 {, as the b4-pawn will be questioned; Black, in his turn, can prevent this advance by playing 8....a5 at once}) 9... a5 $11) (6. Be3 d5 {looks attractive from Black's point of view as well:} 7. Nc3 (7. exd5 Qxd5 (7... Nxd5 8. Nxc6 bxc6 $11) 8. Nxc6 Qxc6 9. O-O Be7 $11) (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Nd2 (8. e5 $6 Nd7 9. f4 Bc5 $15) 8... e5 9. O-O Be7 $11) 7... Bb4 $1 (7... e5 {may objectively be premature, for example} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. exd5 cxd5 10. Bg5 {with some pressure, even though Black should hold after} Bb4 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Re1 h6 14. Bh4 Qe7 (14... e4 $143 15. Bf1) 15. c4 dxc4 16. Bxc4 Qb4 17. Bxf6 Qxc4 18. Bxe5 Bf5 $44 {/=}) 8. exd5 (8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5 d4 10. exf6 dxe3 11. fxg7 exf2+ 12. Kf1 Rg8 $132) 8... Nxd5 9. Nxc6 Nxe3 10. fxe3 bxc6 11. Qg4 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 O-O {and, at the sight of the opponent's ruined structure, Black is at least equal -} 13. O-O Rb8 14. Rad1 Qa5 15. Qe4 g6 16. c4 (16. Qxc6 Bb7) 16... Rb2 $11) 6... dxc6 {The more solid approach of the two.} ({Indeed,} 6... bxc6 $5 {is also fully playable:} 7. Bf4 $5 (7. O-O d5 {The typical for this line central pawn structure has arisen.} 8. e5 (8. Qe2 Be7) (8. Nd2 Bd6 9. Qe2 Qc7 10. h3 O-O 11. c4 Bb7 $11) 8... Nd7 9. Re1 (9. Qe2 a5 10. Re1 Nc5 $11) 9... a5 {[%cal Gc8a6] Yet another common thrust, preparing Bc8-a6:} 10. c4 (10. Nd2 Ba6 11. Bxa6 Rxa6 12. Qg4 $5 ({in reply to} 12. c4 {Black can safely continue with} Be7) 12... Qb8 13. Nf3 g6 $1 {Solving the concrete problem, even more, from g7 the bishop will exert extra pressure on the central pawn -} 14. c4 Bg7 $11) 10... Bb4 {is aimed at neutralizing the potentially dangerous Bc1:} 11. Nc3 (11. Nd2 Ba6 12. a3 ({here} 12. Qg4 {can be answered with} O-O) 12... Bc5 13. Qg4 Qb6 14. Re2 Bd4 $5 15. Qxg7 O-O-O $132) 11... d4 12. a3 Be7 13. Na4 c5 14. Qg4 Kf8 15. b3 $11) (7. c4 d5 8. Nd2 (8. cxd5 cxd5) 8... Bd6 $11) 7... d5 8. Nd2 {is a relatively new approach, to which the best antidote seems to be} g6 $1 ({the humble} 8... Be7 9. O-O {may justify White's set-up, for instance} Nd7 {does not reach its purpose after} 10. Re1 Nc5 11. Bf1 $14) 9. c3 {secures Bf4, it is Black's turn to decide about his dark-squared bishop:} (9. O-O $6 {is imprecise - after} Nh5 $1 {White cannot preserve Bf4 in the board!}) (9. Bg5 h6 (9... Be7 10. Qe2) 10. Bh4 Bd6 {must be a good version of the line 9.c3 Bd6, see below, for Black can safely evacuate his king from the center -} 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 (12. Re1 e5) 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Be7 $11) 9... Nh5 $5 (9... Bg7 10. Qa4 Qb6 11. Bd6 (11. exd5 exd5 {is likely to transpose}) 11... Bf8 12. Be5 Be7 13. exd5 (13. Bd4 Qc7) 13... exd5 14. Bd4 Qc7 15. O-O O-O 16. Rfe1 (16. b4 Nd7) 16... c5 (16... Ng4 $6 17. Rxe7 Qxe7 18. Qxc6 $14) 17. Be5 ({Here the exchange sacrifice} 17. Rxe7 Qxe7 $140 18. Qa3 {, in order to preserve the dominating Bd4, is less dangerous, e.g.} Nd7 19. Nb3 Re8 20. Nxc5 Ne5 (20... Nxc5 21. Bxc5 Qg5 $11 {, followed by activation of Bc8, must be sufficient either, although it makes sense to keep the knight, which may chase the enemy bishops}) 21. Bf1 $11) 17... Qb6 18. c4 Ng4 $1 (18... d4 $143 19. Bxd4 cxd4 20. Rxe7 Qxb2 21. Rd1 Bg4 22. f3 Be6 23. Rxa7 Rxa7 24. Qxa7 Qc3 25. Nb1 Qb2 26. Qa3 Rb8 $14) 19. Nf3 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 d4 $1 {A strong idea from a practical point of view - at the cost of a pawn, Black will have a huge asset in this protected passed pawn.} 21. Nxg6 hxg6 22. Rxe7 Be6 (22... Qxb2 23. Rf1 $14) 23. h4 (23. Qa3 a5) 23... Qxb2 24. Rf1 Qb6 25. h5 Qd6 26. Rxa7 Rxa7 27. Qxa7 Bf5 $44) (9... Bd6 $5 {A possible, though a bit risky continuation:} 10. Bh6 $1 (10. Qf3 e5 11. Bg5 Be7 12. O-O Rb8 13. b4 Be6 14. Nb3 O-O ({Black can also restrict Nb3 by} 14... Nd7) 15. Nc5 {and here the same} Nd7 {seems sufficient,} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Qf6 {, when the threatened e-pawn can be easily defended by} Qd6 {, for instance.}) (10. e5 $6 Nh5 $1 {can spell danger only for White}) 10... e5 11. h3 Bf8 12. Be3 Bg7 13. Bc5 (13. Qa4 O-O 14. Qxc6 Rb8 $44) 13... Bf8 14. Qa4 Bd7 15. Nb3 (15. Qa3 Bxc5 16. Qxc5 Qe7 $11) 15... Bxc5 16. Nxc5 {A small strategical victory for White, but the real battle on the queenside is yet to begin.} O-O 17. O-O a5 $132 {Preparing to undermine the nicely placed Nc5 and the supporting b-pawn. Besides, Black is relying on his mighty pawn center.} 18. Rfe1 Qb6 19. b4 (19. Qa3 Qc7) 19... axb4 20. Qxb4 Qc7 21. a4 Ra5 22. Nb3 Ra7 23. a5 $11) 10. Be3 (10. Be5 $6 f6 11. g4 (11. Bg3 e5 12. O-O Bh6 $15) 11... fxe5 12. gxh5 Rb8 $15) 10... Bd6 {is the critical position for the whole deviation with 6....bxc6:} 11. O-O (11. Nf3 $5 Qc7 12. Qa4 Nf4 13. O-O-O (13. Bf1 dxe4 14. Qxe4 O-O 15. O-O-O Nd5 16. Bh6 Rb8 $132) 13... Nxd3+ (13... Bd7 14. Bf1) 14. Rxd3 Bd7 15. exd5 cxd5 {and now} 16. Qh4 {, based on the weakened dark squares next to Ke8, is double-edged. It is necessary for Black to create threats himself, for example} Qa5 17. Kb1 Bb5 18. Rd2 O-O $5 19. Bd4 f6 {(an obligatory measure against the threatened deadly battery)} 20. Bxf6 Bc4 21. b3 Rab8 $132) ({We have just seen of} 11. Qa4 Qc7 12. Nf3 {in 11.Nf3!?}) 11... O-O (11... Qc7 $143 12. g3 $14) 12. Re1 (12. c4 Bf4 13. Bc5 Re8 $11) (12. b4 $6 {, as in Lavrencic - Lagarde, Tegernsee, 2023, fails to impress because of} a5 $1 13. a3 Nf4 $15) 12... e5 {with mutual chances:} 13. b4 (13. Be2 Ng7 14. Qa4 Bd7 15. Nb3 Ne6 16. Qa6 Qc7 17. exd5 cxd5 18. Rad1 d4 19. cxd4 exd4 20. Nxd4 Bxh2+ 21. Kh1 Be5 $11) (13. Bh6 Re8 $13) (13. Rc1 f5 $5 (13... Ng7 14. exd5 cxd5 15. c4 d4 16. Bh6 Rb8 17. c5 Bc7 $132) 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Bxf5 Rxf5 16. c4 (16. g4 $2 {is refuted by} Nf4) 16... d4 17. Bh6 Bb4 $5 {(preparing to get rid of the best blockading piece)} 18. g4 ({in case of} 18. a3 Bxd2 19. Bxd2 Qf6 20. Qe2 Nf4 $11 {White will not enjoy the possession of the e4-outpost for long}) 18... Bf8 $1 {(a neat tactical point)} 19. Bxf8 (19. gxf5 Bxh6 {with plenty of compensation}) 19... Rxf8 20. gxh5 Qg5+ 21. Kf1 Qh4 {, when repeating moves by} 22. Kg1 Qg5+ 23. Kf1 Qh4 $11 {is a reasonable decision for White}) {requires urgent measures, e.g.} 13... d4 $1 ({White's plan is revealed by} 13... Qc7 14. Nb3 {establishing control over the c5-height, for instance} Rd8 15. Qc2 f5 16. exd5 cxd5 17. Bc5 $14) 14. Bh6 (14. cxd4 Bxb4 15. Rb1 a5 16. a3 exd4 17. Bh6 Bc3 $132) 14... dxc3 15. Nc4 Bxb4 16. Nxe5 c2 17. Qxc2 Bxe1 18. Bxf8 Bxf2+ 19. Qxf2 Qxf8 20. Bc4 Be6 21. Bxe6 fxe6 $11) 7. Nd2 (7. Qf3 e5 8. Nd2 {is arguably an improvement, as shown by} Bc5 9. Nc4 O-O 10. O-O (10. Nxe5 $2 Re8 $17) (10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 $11) 10... b5 ({now the central pawn is poisoned, but there is nothing wrong with protecting it by} 10... Qc7 11. Bg5 Be7 12. h3 Be6 $11) 11. Ne3 a5 12. a4 b4 13. Nc4 Bd4 14. h3 Ba6 $11) (7. O-O e5 8. a4 (8. Nd2 {leads us back to the text, while}) (8. f4 $2 {is typically met by} Bc5+ 9. Kh1 Ng4 $17) 8... Bc5 9. Nd2 Be6 ({or} 9... O-O {at first}) 10. Qe2 (10. Nf3 Qc7) 10... O-O 11. h3 {So far Yuffa - Gelfand, Vrnjacka Banja, 2023, when pretty safe is} h6 12. Nf3 Qc7 13. Bd2 (13. Bc4 Rfe8) 13... Rfe8 14. a5 (14. Bc3 Bd6) 14... Rad8 $11) 7... e5 8. O-O (8. Nc4 {does not contain a threat, so Black can confidently play} Be6) 8... Bc5 9. Nb3 ({White can hardly do without} 9. a4 {, so it is natural to continue with it, the following sample line} O-O 10. Nb3 Bd6 11. Qe2 h6 12. Be3 Be6 13. Bc4 (13. Nc5 Bc8) (13. a5 Qe7) 13... Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qc7 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 $11 {strongly resembles the leading text}) (9. Nc4 {makes more sense now, the position remains balanced after} Qc7 (9... Qe7 10. a4 O-O) 10. Bg5 (10. Qf3 O-O 11. Qg3 {Instead, 11.Bg5 has been mentioned in the notes to 7.Qf3.} Re8 12. Bg5 Nd7 $11) 10... Be7 11. a4 Be6 12. Qf3 O-O 13. Ne3 h6 14. Bxf6 (14. Bh4 Nh7 $11) 14... Bxf6 15. Bc4 Bxc4 16. Nxc4 Bg5 $11) 9... Bd6 ({The other retreat} 9... Bb6 10. a4 a5 11. Nd2 Be6 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Nc4 Bc7 {looks solid, but the crafty} 14. b3 $1 {, intending to meet 14....Nd7 with 15.Ba3!, is still posing problems and the impatient} b5 15. Nd2 Bg4 16. Nf3 $14 {, as in Grischuk - Gelfand, Amsterdam 2023, is probably not Black's best bet.}) 10. Qe2 O-O 11. a4 Be6 12. Bc4 Bxc4 13. Qxc4 h6 14. Rd1 Qc7 15. Bd2 $11 *

