1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bc4 (6. f3 {is rarely effective, when Black can push his central pawn to d5 in one go:} Bb4 (6... d5 $5 7. exd5 (7. Bb5 Bd7) 7... Nxd5 8. Nxd5 exd5 $11) 7. a3 (7. Be3 $6 d5 $15) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 d5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bg5 O-O $11 {without any fear of} 11. e5 {because of the counterstrike} Qc7 $1) (6. Be3 Bb4 7. Bd3 e5 $5 ({Black is absolutely fine after} 7... d5 $11 {, as we already know from the previous Chapter}) 8. Nxc6 bxc6 (8... dxc6 $11) 9. O-O O-O 10. a3 (10. f4 d5 $1) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 d5 $11 {, once again with Black's tremendous central activity}) (6. Bg5 {is overprotecting the central pawn, but, as soon as Black is by no means obliged to play d7-d6, the text move is lacking other notable merits:} h6 {at once opens new horizons, e.g.} (6... Bb4 $5 {is quite typical for the featured 4 Knights Variation:} 7. Qd3 (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Qf3 (8. e5 $2 Qa5 $17) 8... h6 9. Bd2 d5 $132) 7... h6 {(a useful interpolation)} 8. Bh4 Qa5 (8... Ne5 $5 9. Qb5 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Ng6) 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nb3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qc7 $11) 7. Bh4 Bc5 $5 ({a reasonable and very ambitious attempt at using the absence of Bc1 from the queenside;} 7... Bb4 8. Qd3 {transposes to 7.Qd3 from above}) 8. Nxc6 (8. Nb3 Be7) 8... bxc6 {and now:} 9. Bd3 (9. e5 Qb6 $1 10. Na4 ({a big point of Black's move order is revealed by} 10. exf6 $2 Qxb2 $19) 10... Qb4+ 11. c3 Qe4+ 12. Be2 Bf8 $1 ({the dark-squared bishops are quite valuable in this unusual position, as witnessed by} 12... Qxe5 13. Bg3 Qf5 14. Nxc5 Qxc5 15. Bd6 Qd5 16. c4 Qxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Ne4 18. Ba3 $44) 13. Bg3 (13. Qd4 Qxd4 14. cxd4 Nd5 $132) 13... Nh5 14. f3 {(saving the own bishop as well)} Qd5 15. Qxd5 cxd5 16. Bf2 Nf4 17. Bf1 Ng6 18. Bd4 {and here Black can switch to a siege of the central e5-pawn in the spirit of the Berlin endgame by} h5 $132 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) (9. Qf3 d5 10. O-O-O Be7 $132) 9... e5 {The most solid reply with good prospects on the dark squares, as shown by} 10. O-O a5 11. Kh1 (11. Na4 Bd4) 11... g5 12. Bg3 d6 13. Na4 Ba7 $132 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) ({A move like} 6. Nb3 {can be considered a preparation for g2-g4 at best, but it cannot objectively pretend for much.} Bb4 (6... d5 $5 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Re8 $11) 7. Bd3 O-O ({or} 7... Ne5 {at once}) 8. O-O Ne5 9. f4 Nxd3 10. cxd3 (10. Qxd3 d6) 10... b6 $11) (6. h3 {is idle and Black can try to seize the initiative by means of the consistent} Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bd2 d5 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Bxc3 ({both} 10... a5) ({and} 10... Bd6 {are reliable continuations, but there is no particular reason to avoid the forced line in the text}) 11. Bxc3 dxe4 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Bxe4 Ba6 14. Re1 Qxb2 $11 {/}) (6. g4 {is in fact sacrificing (or losing?) a pawn:} d5 {Following the famous principle for a central counterstrike in reply to a flank diversion - in comparison to the Keres attack here Black has an extra (Nb8-c6) move:} (6... Nxg4 7. Qxg4 (7. Nxc6 $2 Qh4 $1 $17 {is the point}) 7... Nxd4 8. Bd3 {and White has to prove compensation. He can claim it in the end of the sample line} Qf6 9. f4 Bc5 10. e5 h5 11. Qg3 Qh4 12. Qxh4 Nf3+ 13. Ke2 Nxh4 14. Nb5 O-O 15. Be3 b6 16. Bxc5 bxc5 17. Nd6 $44 {, which can be certainly improved from Black's perspective}) 7. exd5 (7. g5 Nxe4 8. Nxe4 (8. Nxc6 $6 Nxc3) 8... dxe4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 bxc6 11. Bg2 h6 12. Bxe4 Bb7 $11) (7. Nxc6 $6 bxc6 8. g5 Nd7 $17) 7... Nxd5 8. Bg2 Qb6 9. Nxd5 (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. O-O Ba6 11. Re1 Rd8 $132) 9... exd5 10. Nb3 ({White can still preserve the g4-pawn by} 10. Nf5 {, to which very interesting is} Qa6 $132 11. Qxd5 $6 Be6) 10... Qb4+ 11. c3 Qxg4 12. O-O Be7 $11) 6... Qc7 {A logical idea to play in the spirit of the Taimanov.} ({Possible is} 6... Bb4 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 Nxe4 $13 {with complicated play. After 9.Bd3 at once or with a preliminary trade of Nc6, the game can be transposed to Chapter 6, in which the consequences of 6 are presented.Be2 Bb4 are explored. In addition, the temporary piece sacrifice} 9. Qg4 O-O 10. Qxe4 d5 {with approximate equality due to the opposite-coloured bishops after} 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qf3 {should be noted.}) (6... d5 $5 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. exd5 exd5 9. O-O Be7 $11) 7. O-O (7. Bb3 $6 {can run into} Nxe4 $1 8. Nxe4 Qe5 9. Be3 Qxe4 10. O-O Be7 $15) (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Qe2 {does not disable the break} d5 9. exd5 $140 cxd5 10. Bxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qa5+ 12. Nc3 Bb4 (12... Ba6 13. Qe4 Rc8 $44) 13. Qf3 (13. Bd2 Ba6) 13... O-O 14. O-O Ba6 15. Rd1 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Rad8 $11) (7. Ncb5 {is bizarre - the x-Ray along the c-file will instantly disappear, but such jumps are definitely time-consuming and Black should be fine:} Qb8 (7... Qb6 8. Be3 Bc5 9. c3 O-O 10. b4 Bxd4 11. Nxd4 Ne5 12. Bb3 Neg4 13. e5 Nxe3 14. fxe3 Ne8 15. Qh5 Qc7 16. Rc1 d6 (16... f6 $5) 17. exd6 Nxd6 $11) 8. Bd3 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 Ne5 $11) 7... Nxd4 $5 (7... a6 {is consequent, but Black is trying to skip it as longer as possible}) (7... Be7 {can also correspond to his flexible strategy.}) 8. Qxd4 Bc5 9. Qd2 {White should already be on alert, for example:} (9. Nb5 Qc6 $132) (9. Qd3 $6 Ng4 10. Qg3 Qxg3 11. hxg3 d6 12. Be2 h5 $15) (9. Qd1 a6 10. a4 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 11. Bd3 Bb7 $11) 9... O-O 10. Qe2 (10. Qg5 {has more aggressive intentions, now worth checking is the sharp opportunity} Bd6 $5 ({a plan with} 10... d6 11. Qg3 Bd4 {is yet to be explored, here Black is able to restrict the bishops with solid blockade after} 12. Bd3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 e5 14. Bg5 Ne8 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gf7f6]}) 11. Bd3 Bxh2+ 12. Kh1 h6 13. Qh4 Be5 14. Bxh6 (14. f4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 d5 16. e5 Ne4 17. Ba3 Re8 $132) 14... gxh6 15. f4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nh7 $1 {and now:} 17. Rf3 (17. Qxh6 f6 18. e5 d6 19. Rf3 f5 20. Rg3+ Kh8 21. exd6 Qf7 22. Bxf5 (22. Re1 Rg8) 22... exf5 23. Re1 Be6 24. Rxe6 Rae8 25. Reg6 Rg8 $132) 17... Qxc3 18. e5 $5 {A fascinating idea to cut the way back of Qc3, but it is objectively not enough for more than a draw, as demonstrated by} Qxa1+ 19. Kh2 f5 20. Qxh6 Kf7 (20... Kh8 21. Rh3 Rf7 22. Qg6 Rg7 23. Qe8+ Rg8 $11 {is an easier road to fixing the logical outcome}) 21. Qxh7+ Ke8 22. Qh4 $3 {It is obligatory to stop the evacuation of the enemy king to the queenside. As the latter is undeveloped, Black's extra material is not felt, and even he must tread carefully.} Qd1 ({a necessary precauion;} 22... Rg8 $4 {fails exactly to} 23. Be2 $1 $18) 23. Rg3 {and a repetition like 24.Rg7 Rf7 25.Rg8 Rf8 26.Rg7 is in the air.}) 10... d6 11. Bg5 {The most active continuation:} (11. Nb5 Qb6 (11... Qc6 12. Bd3 Nd7 $11) 12. Bd3 (12. Nxd6 Bxd6 13. e5 Be7 14. exf6 Bxf6 $11) 12... Nd7 13. c3 a6 14. Nd4 Ne5 15. Rd1 Qc7 $11) (11. Bf4 a6 {Time has come for this prophylaxis against the possible jumps.} 12. Rad1 (12. e5 dxe5 13. Bxe5 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Rfd1 Qc7 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Bd7 $11) 12... e5 13. Bg5 Bg4 14. Qd2 Qd8 $1 (14... Bxd1 $2 {will cost dearly after} 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nd5 Qd8 17. Qh6 $18) 15. Rde1 h6 {with balanced play -} 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Nd5 Qg5 18. Qxg5 hxg5 19. b4 Ba7 20. Bb3 Kh7 $11 {[%cal Gg4e6]}) 11... Nd7 12. a4 (12. Bb3 a6) 12... a6 13. Bb3 Bd4 $5 {The position is more or less resembling the Sozin attack. The main difference can be seen in the location of Bc5, and here is an original concept for trading it for Nc3 at a proper moment, with the idea of pressing on the e4-pawn.} (13... Rb8 $5 14. Rad1 $140 h6 15. Bh4 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 Ba6 $44) 14. Qd2 (14. Rad1 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Nc5 $11) 14... Be5 ({Black can initiate immediate counterplay against the central pawn by means of} 14... Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Qxc3 16. bxc3 Nc5 17. f3 d5 {and, as usual, the presence of opposite-coloured bishops is a precondition for a draw, as shown by} 18. exd5 (18. Be7 $144 Nxb3) 18... Nxb3 19. cxb3 exd5 $11) 15. Rad1 Nc5 16. Bh4 {A very sophisticated prophylactic measure.} ({The straightforward} 16. f4 {is surprisingly met by} Bxc3 17. Qxc3 b5 $1 18. f5 (18. axb5 Qa7 $1 {is the hidden tactical finesse, which dooms the central e4-pawn; the textmove 16.Bh4 is directed exactly against it}) 18... bxa4 19. Ba2 Qa7 20. Qf3 (20. Be3 Nxe4 21. Qd3 Qb7 22. f6 gxf6 23. Bh6 Qb6+ 24. Qd4 Qxd4+ 25. Rxd4 Bb7 26. Bxf8 Kxf8 27. Rxa4 a5 $44) 20... Nxe4+ 21. Be3 Qb7 22. Rd4 d5 (22... exf5 $5 23. Bd5 Qb8 24. Bxa8 Qxa8 25. Rxd6 Be6 $44 {and Black has again plenty of compensation for the exchange}) 23. fxe6 Bxe6 24. c4 Nd6 25. cxd5 Bd7 26. Qf4 Rae8 $11) 16... b6 17. f4 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Bb7 19. f5 ({It is hard to defend the hanging central pawn, e.g.} 19. Rfe1 Rac8) 19... Bxe4 20. Bg3 e5 21. f6 Rfc8 22. Qe3 Nxb3 23. cxb3 (23. Qxe4 $143 Qxc2) 23... Qc5 24. Qxc5 Rxc5 (24... dxc5 25. fxg7 Re8 26. Rf6 Rab8 27. Rd7 Bg6 $11 {is safe enough.}) 25. Rxd6 Rc2 26. Rf2 Rc1+ $11 *

