1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Qd3 d5 $1 {The same vigorous reaction as against the queen sally on the previous move.} 7. exd5 ({An amusing line goes on with} 7. Bg5 dxe4 8. Nxc6 exd3 9. Nxd8 dxc2 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Bd3 h6 12. Be3 Bd7 13. Bxc2 Bc6 $11) 7... Nb4 $1 {In this jump, especially in the next intermediate move, we can find the tactical justification of Black's brave move order.  Taking the pawn back at once fails to impress:} (7... Nxd5 $6 8. Nxd5 exd5 (8... Qxd5 {is avoiding an isolated d5-pawn, but Black seems in trouble after} 9. Nb5 $1 Qe5+ 10. Qe3 {, for instance} Qb8 11. Qg3 e5 12. Be3 Be6 13. O-O-O $16) 9. Be3 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) (7... exd5 $6 {is met by the same plan} 8. Be3 $1 Be7 9. O-O-O {e.g.} O-O 10. f3 Re8 11. Qd2 $14) 8. Qg3 {As already mentioned, the usual follow-up of Qd1-d3, here are the rest in brief:} (8. Qc4 Be7 $1 ({in comparison to the other moves by Qd3, here its awkward location is a vote for} 8... Nbxd5) 9. Bg5 ({a blunder is} 9. dxe6 $2 Qxd4 $1 10. exf7+ Kf8 $19) 9... exd5 $5 (9... Nbxd5 10. Nxd5 (10. O-O-O Bd7 $5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11) 10... Nxd5 (10... Qxd5 11. Qxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxe7 Kxe7 $11) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. g3 (12. O-O-O O-O 13. g3 b6 $11) 12... e5 13. Nb3 Nb6 14. Qe4 O-O $11) 10. Qe2 (10. Qb3 Nc6 11. Bb5 O-O 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxc6 Be6 $132) 10... O-O 11. O-O-O Bd7 12. a3 Nc6 $132) (8. Qf3 Bc5 $1 9. a3 (9. Bb5+ $6 Bd7) 9... Nbxd5 10. Nb3 (10. Nxd5 Qxd5 $11) 10... Bb6 11. Bd2 Bd7 12. O-O-O Bc6 13. Qg3 {must be compared to 8.Qg3 in the leading text - here, White has succeeded to the castle to the long, but at the cost of some time, including misplacing his Nd4. Black is, therefore, fine, for instance} O-O 14. Bd3 Qc7 $11) 8... Bc5 $1 {The second big point! The recaptures can wait again:} (8... Nbxd5 $6 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Bd2 $14) (8... a6 $6 9. Bg5 Nbxd5 10. O-O-O $14) 9. a3 ({It is important to understand that losing castling rights after} 9. Bb5+ Kf8 {does not really hurt Black, the tournament practice has confirmed that assessment, for example} 10. a3 (10. Nce2 a6 11. Bc4 Nbxd5 $132) 10... Nbxd5 11. Nde2 (11. Nb3 Bd6 12. Qf3 Qc7 $132) 11... Bd7 $1 {, solving the problem with Bc8 with interest:} 12. Bxd7 (12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. Nxc3 Bc6 14. O-O h5 $1 $132) (12. O-O {is inviting} h5 $1 13. Qf3 h4 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. h3 (15. Rd1 {transposes to the next line}) 15... Rc8 $11) 12... Qxd7 13. O-O ({the careless} 13. Nxd5 $2 {was mercilessly refuted by} Ne4 $1 $19 {in Harikrishna - Vitiugov, Belgrade, 2022}) 13... h5 $5 (13... Rd8 $11 {had been played in Tari - Vidit, chess24.com INT, 2021, even though we have just seen that rook belongs to the c8-square as well}) 14. Rd1 h4 15. Qf3 Rh5 16. Ne4 Qc7 $11) 9... Nbxd5 (9... Bxd4 $2 10. axb4 $16) 10. Nxd5 (10. Bb5+ Kf8 {- 9.Bb5.}) 10... Qxd5 {Taking advantage of the fact the g7-pawn is immune.} (10... exd5 $143 $6 11. Qe5+ Kf8 (11... Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. Be3 Bb6 14. f3 $14) 12. Be3 $14) 11. Nb5 O-O {Neutralizing the double threat most logically.} ({Black should better refrain from} 11... Ne4 12. Nc7+ Kf8 13. Qh4 $5 ({a start of a curious sequence; White can also opt for a risk-free edge in the ending after} 13. Nxd5 Nxg3 14. hxg3 exd5 15. Be2 $14) 13... Bxf2+ 14. Qxf2 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Qxc7 16. Bb4+ Kg8 17. Qd4 a5 18. O-O-O Bd7 19. Bxa5 Qxa5 20. Qxe4 Bc6 21. Qe3 $14) (11... Qe4+ $2 12. Be3 $16) 12. Nc3 Qd6 $1 {A subtle retreat.} (12... Qh5 {has been tested before, but it puts Her Majesty in a delicate situation -} 13. Be2 Qf5 (13... Qg6 14. Bd3 Qxg3 15. hxg3 {transposes to Esipenko - Vallejo Pons, see below}) 14. Bd3 Qh5 15. Ne4 $5 ({a possible improvement upon} 15. h3 Bd7 16. Bg5 Be7 17. Be2 Qg6 18. Bd3 Qh5 19. O-O Bc6 $11 {Ter Sahakyan - Erigaisi, Chennai, 2022}) 15... Be7 16. h4 h6 17. Bf4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Bf6 19. c3 e5 20. Be3 a5 21. Rd1 Be6 $11) 13. Bd3 {The most natural continuation compared to:} (13. Bf4 $6 Qb6 $15) ({in case of} 13. Bg5 Qxg3 14. hxg3 {worth checking is} Ng4 $5 15. f3 $140 h6 $11) (13. Be2 Qxg3 14. hxg3 e5 $1 15. Bg5 Bd4 16. Bxf6 (16. Nd1 Be6 $11) 16... Bxc3+ ({more simple and consequent than} 16... gxf6) 17. bxc3 gxf6 18. O-O-O Be6 19. Bd3 Rac8 20. Rxh7 Rxc3 21. Rdh1 f5 {with a logical draw by repetition after} 22. Rh8+ Kg7 23. R1h7+ Kg6 24. Rh6+ Kg7 25. R6h7+ $11) 13... h6 $1 $146 {Here comes the second refinement.} ({Known is} 13... Qxg3 14. hxg3 h6 15. f3 $14 {Esipenko - Vallejo Pons, Baku, 2023}) (13... Rd8 {might be also better than the immediate trade of the queens.}) 14. Bf4 (14. Qxd6 Bxd6 15. Ne4 Be7 $11) 14... Qb6 $1 {An important point - Black is holding by tactical means.} (14... e5 $6 15. Be3) 15. Bxh6 {Relatively the best, though it leads by force to a balanced endgame.} (15. Bd2 {can hardly challenge Black, for example} Bd7 ({more complicated is} 15... Bd6 16. Qh4 Be7 17. O-O-O {with mutual chances after} Rd8 $11 {; the move order in the text is depriving White of the aggressive plan with castling to the long}) 16. O-O Bd6 17. Qh4 Rfc8 18. Rfe1 ({the second player should not be worried by} 18. Bxh6 $6 Qxb2) 18... Be7 19. Be3 (19. Qg3 Bd6 $11 {might result in a repetition}) 19... Bc5 20. Bxc5 Rxc5 $11) (15. Na4 Qa5+ 16. b4 Qxa4 17. Bxh6 Nh5 (17... Bxb4+ $5 18. Ke2 Nh5 19. Qh4 e5 20. axb4 Qc6 $11) 18. Qe5 Bb6 19. Qxh5 gxh6 {and White must reconcile himself with a draw by perpetual check after} 20. Qxh6 f5 $11) 15... Bxf2+ 16. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Ng4+ 18. Kg3 Nxh6 19. Rad1 b6 ({Possible is also} 19... Bd7 20. Bh7+ Kxh7 21. Rxd7 b5 $11 22. Nxb5 $140 Rab8) 20. Be4 (20. Rd2 Bb7 21. Rhd1 Rfc8 $11) 20... Rb8 21. Rhe1 a6 22. h3 b5 $11 *

