1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. g3 d5 (6... Bb4 $5 {is probably less to the point here, for White is ready to defend his central pawn -} 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O {Still,} d6 $5 {, which stops the positional threat 9.Nxc6 e5, deserves practical tests. As we have seen in Chapter 2, exchanging Nc3 for a bishop is an additional option.}) 7. exd5 ({In reply to} 7. Bg2 {Black can refine the idea from above with the help of the intermediate} Bc5 $1 8. Nb3 Bb4 {and now:} 9. O-O (9. exd5 exd5 ({from a practical point of view it is better to refrain from} 9... Nxd5 $5 {, when White is obtaining a standard playing compensation for the sacrificed pawn after} 10. O-O Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3 12. Ba3 Qxd1 13. Raxd1 Bf6 $11 {[%cal Gf6e7]}) 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O {is examined below under 9.0-0 Bxc3 10.exd5 exd5}) 9... Bxc3 10. exd5 ({White's compensation after} 10. bxc3 Nxe4 {is questionable, for instance} 11. c4 (11. Ba3 $143 Nd6 $1 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Ge8g8]}) 11... O-O 12. Bb2 a5 $11) 10... exd5 11. bxc3 O-O 12. Re1 h6 {and Black is pretty solid -} 13. Qd3 Re8 14. Bf4 Re7 $5 {[%cal Gd8e8]} ({a clever way to fight for the e-file; among the various alternatives,} 14... b6 {is a useful step towards mobilizing the queenside}) 15. a4 (15. Nd4 Bd7) 15... Qe8 16. Rxe7 Qxe7 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Qxd4 Bf5 $11) 7... exd5 (7... Nxd5 {looks natural, but White retains some queenside pressure after} 8. Bg2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bd7 10. O-O (10. Rb1 Qc8 {does not bring any change}) 10... Be7 11. Rb1 Qc8 $13) 8. Bg2 Bg4 $1 {The key move in Black's move order!} 9. Nde2 {Probably the best answer:} (9. Nce2 Bc5 $11) (9. Qd2 $6 Qe7+ $1 10. Kf1 Qd7 $15) (9. f3 {is already a concession -} Bd7 10. O-O (10. Be3 Bb4) 10... Be7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Nb3 Re8 13. Bf2 Bf5 14. Re1 (14. g4 Be6 15. h3 Bd6 16. Qd2 Qb8 $132) 14... h5 $11) ({An important line is} 9. Qd3 Bc5 10. Be3 (10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. O-O O-O $11) (10. Nb3 Qe7+ 11. Be3 O-O $11) (10. Qe3+ Ne7 $1 11. O-O O-O 12. Qd3 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Nc6 14. Qc5 d4 $11) 10... Qb6 {(continuing inevitably in the same energetic style - nearly every Black move contains a threat!)} 11. h3 (11. Nxc6 Bxe3 12. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 13. fxe3 bxc6 $11) 11... Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Qxd4 13. hxg4 Qxd3 14. cxd3 Nxg4 $11) 9... Bb4 10. h3 (10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O {may transpose after} 12. h3 (12. f3 $6 Bd7 13. g4 Rc8 $15) {, but in this sequence Black can also consider} 12... Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Rc8 ({both} 13... h6) ({and} 13... Qa5 {are sound alternatives}) 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11) 10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Bf5 $1 12. Rb1 ({Similar is} 12. O-O Be4 $5 {, following the general idea to neutralize or at least compel the f-pawn to the 3rd rank, Black is fine in case of} 13. Bxe4 (13. f3 Bg6 14. Rb1 O-O {goes to the main text}) 13... dxe4 14. Bg5 O-O $11) ({no better is} 12. g4 Be4 13. f3 Bg6 $11) (12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxd5 O-O 15. O-O Bxc2 16. Qd2 Ba4 $11) 12... Be4 13. f3 Bg6 14. Rxb7 O-O 15. O-O Qa5 16. Bg5 (16. a3 Qa4 $11) 16... Qxa2 17. Nf4 ({Here is the first and probably the best opportunity for inserting} 17. Bxf6 gxf6 {, though Black is able to repel} 18. f4 {with the common} Be4 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Qd7 Qxc2 21. Qg4+ Kh8 {and} 22. Qh4 {is sufficient only for a draw by perpetual after} Qxe2 23. Qxf6+ Kg8 24. Qg5+ $11) 17... Rfd8 18. Qa1 ({In case of} 18. Bxf6 gxf6 {it is difficult to suggest anything else than the same} 19. Qa1) 18... Qc4 {Postponing the trade of the queens to a more appropriate moment.} (18... Qxa1 $143 19. Rxa1 Bxc2 20. Ra2 $44) 19. Rf2 Qc5 20. Nd3 Bxd3 21. cxd3 d4 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. c4 {At first sight, such position of Benoni type must favor White, but his passed pawn is blockaded and} Rab8 {initiates counterplay along the b-file, which, in combination with the marching a-pawn, should guarantee equality, for example} 24. Rxb8 Rxb8 25. f4 a5 $11 *

