1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. a3 Be7 (6... d5 $5 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. exd5 exd5 9. O-O Be7 {is a probable option either}) (6... d6 7. Be3 Be7 {is a normal developing plan, albeit not as flexible as the text.}) 7. Be3 (7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. Be3 {is back to the leading line}) (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 {strongly resembles the main tabiya of the featured 4 Knights Variation, but with 6.a3 Be7 being played in advance. The latter should suit Black for the least reason he can already castle, here are several sample lines:} 9. Qg4 {Trying to exploit the only visible drawback of 6...Be7 -} (9. Ne4 Qa5+ $1 10. c3 (10. Bd2 Qc7 11. f4 f5 $1 $132) 10... O-O 11. Bd3 (11. Be2 f6 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. O-O d5 15. Be3 Ba6 $11) 11... Qc7 12. f4 f5 {Black is fine after this thematic strike, e.g.} 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Nxf6+ Rxf6 15. Qe2 (15. Qc2 g6 16. Be3 c5 $132) 15... Bb7 16. Be3 c5 17. O-O-O Rb8 $132) (9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Bd3 Ba6 $132) 9... g6 {is practically forced, the game can continue with:} 10. Bd2 (10. Qg3 d6 11. Ne4 (11. Nxd5 exd5 $5 12. Bh6 $140 Be6 $11) (11. Bh6 Qb6 12. O-O-O Nxc3 13. Qxc3 d5 14. h4 Rb8 $132) 11... dxe5 12. c4 (12. Qxe5 f6 13. Qg3 f5 14. Nc3 Bd6 $132) 12... Nf4 13. Qc3 O-O 14. Qxe5 Nd3+ 15. Bxd3 Qxd3 16. Nf6+ Bxf6 17. Qxf6 {and Black is just in time for} Rd8 18. f3 Ba6 19. Bh6 Qd4 $11) 10... h5 $146 (10... Rb8 11. Na4) 11. Qe4 (11. Qe2 d6 12. exd6 Qxd6 13. O-O-O Rb8 $132) 11... d6 {A timely undermining of the center.} 12. exd6 (12. O-O-O Rb8 $132) (12. Na4 O-O 13. c4 Nb6 14. Nxb6 Qxb6 15. exd6 Bxd6 16. O-O-O e5 17. Be3 Qc7 18. c5 Be7 $11) 12... Qxd6 13. Bc4 O-O 14. O-O (14. O-O-O Rb8 $132) 14... Rd8 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c5]}) (7. Bf4 {is usually played on the previous move, see Chapter 7 for the details, after} d6 {the jump Nd4-b5 is simply bad, so White can try to confuse the opponent by} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5 Nd5 10. exd6 Bf6 $5 ({much more interesting than} 10... Nxf4 11. dxe7 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Kxe7 {, which is probably balanced, e.g.} 13. Rd4 Nd5 14. Rc4 Kd6 $11 {, even though White can hope to make use of his better structure}) 11. Bd2 Rb8 12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qxd6 {As a result, Black is practically a pawn up on the kingside; his chances in the long run are not worse, for instance} 15. O-O c5 16. Qh5 (16. Bb5+ Ke7) 16... Ba6 17. c4 (17. Bxa6 Qxa6 18. Qxc5 Rc8 $11) 17... h6 18. Rad1 Qe7 19. Rfe1 O-O 20. Re3 Rfd8 21. Rde1 Rbc8 22. Rg3 Kf8 $11) 7... O-O 8. Be2 (8. Qe2 d5 $132) ({Curious is} 8. f4 e5 $5 (8... d6 {is a normal Scheveningen, which, however, may not be to everyone's taste}) 9. Nxc6 (9. fxe5 Nxe5 $132) 9... dxc6 10. f5 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 b5 ({the concrete} 11... g6 $5 12. Bd3 Re8 {can seriously challenge the early advance of the f-pawn}) 12. Bd3 {So far Nakamura - Dubov, Chess.com INT, 2023,} Bb7 13. Ke2 h5 $11) 8... d6 (8... d5 $143 9. exd5 exd5 10. f3 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2]}) 9. Qd3 $5 ({After} 9. Qd2 {Black can shift to Classical Sicilian with} e5 $1 10. Nf3 (10. Nb3 {allows the stunning temporary piece sacrifice} Nxe4 $1 11. Nxe4 d5 $132 {So - Kramnik, Amsterdam, 2023}) 10... Be6 11. O-O (11. Ng5 Bd7 {may result in a repetition}) 11... h6 $11) (9. O-O Qc7 (9... e5 $5 10. Nb3 Be6 {is worth checking again, but, regarding the commitment of Ke1, Black can stick to a typical Scheveningen middlegame}) 10. f4 ({the same observation belongs to both} 10. Qe1 Bd7) ({and} 10. Kh1 a6 {, see 11.Bxd4 below}) 10... Nxd4 $1 (10... a6 11. Qe1 {may also lead to a heavy theoretical discussion, e.g.} Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Qg3 Bb7 {etc.}) 11. Bxd4 (11. Qxd4 b6 $1 (11... e5 $143 $6 12. Qd2) 12. Bf3 (12. Kh1 Bb7 13. f5 e5 14. Qd3 Rac8 $132) 12... Ba6 13. Rfd1 Rac8 $11) 11... e5 {Here this push, with White's queen still on its initial square, is justified, e.g.} 12. Be3 a6 ({in case of the direct} 12... exf4 13. Rxf4 Be6 {extra option like} 14. Nb5 Qd7 $132 {must be taken into account}) 13. Kh1 exf4 14. Bxf4 Be6 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf6d7,Gd7e5]}) 9... Bd7 {Black keeps on developing while spending time on a7-a6 and Qd8-c7.} ({Besides,} 9... a6 {is fully possible,}) ({but} 9... e5 10. Nb3 $14 {is less to the point in the view of White's better control (Qd3 Rd1 instead of 0-0) over the key d5-square.}) 10. f4 (10. O-O-O {, as well as other schemes with castling to the long, will normally initiate mutual assaults against the opponent's monarch.} Ne5 11. Qd2 Rc8 {is a natural reaction, here are several illustrative lines:} 12. f3 (12. Kb1 a6 13. f3 d5 14. f4 (14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 exd5 $11) 14... Nc4 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 16. e5 Ng4 17. Bg1 Nh6 18. h3 b5 19. b3 Rc8 $132) 12... d5 $1 13. exd5 (13. f4 $6 Nc4 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. e5 Ng4 16. Bg1 b5 $1 17. h3 Nh6 $15) 13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Nb5 Bf5 $1 16. c3 Qa5 17. Qxd5 Bxa3 $1 18. Qxe5 Rxc3+ $1 19. Qxc3 Bb4 20. Qxb4 Qxb4 21. Nd6 Bg6 22. Rd4 Qb3 23. Kd2 a5 24. Rc1 a4 25. Ne4 Qxb2+ 26. Rc2 Qa1 27. Rc1 $11) 10... e5 $1 {Here this thematic blow is once again well-timed.} 11. Nxc6 (11. Nb3 exf4 12. Bxf4 Ne5 13. Qe3 Ng6 14. Bg3 Ng4 $11) (11. Nf3 Ng4 $1 12. Bc1 Re8 (12... Qb6 13. Rf1) (12... f5 $5) 13. h3 Nf6 $132) (11. Nf5 $6 Bxf5 12. exf5 d5 $1 13. fxe5 Nxe5 $15) (11. Ndb5 $5 {can be answered with an analogous jump on the opposite wing, but Black can also make use of the same square by the original} Bg4 $5 12. O-O-O ({after} 12. Bxg4 Nxg4 13. Nd5 {, with an emphasis on the d5-height, Black can force matters by opening the center -} Nxe3 14. Qxe3 exf4 15. Qxf4 Bg5 16. Qf2 Ne7 17. Nbc3 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 f5 $1 $132 19. O-O {Forced and the following simplifications to approximate equality after} fxe4 20. Qd4 Bf6 21. Nxf6+ Rxf6 22. Qd5+ Kh8 23. Qxb7 Rb8 24. Qxa7 Rxb2) 12... a6 13. Nxd6 Bxe2 14. Nxe2 Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Nxe4 16. Qxd8 Raxd8 17. Bb6 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 exf4 19. Nxf4 (19. Rd7 g5 $1 20. Rxb7 Rc8 $132) 19... g5 20. Ne2 f5 $11) 11... bxc6 12. O-O ({Determining the central pawn structure by} 12. fxe5 dxe5 {does not achieve much -} 13. h3 (13. O-O {is strongly met by} Ng4 $1 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 15. Qc4 Qb8 $11 {Urazayev - Kurmangaliyeva, Belgrade, 2023}) 13... Be6 14. O-O h5 $5 15. Qa6 $140 Qc8 $11) (12. O-O-O {is inviting the same sally -} Ng4 $1 13. Bxg4 Bxg4 14. Rd2 Qa5 $132) 12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Bg4 $1 $146 ({The practice has seen the standard Scheveningen regrouping} 13... Be6 14. Qg3 Nd7 15. Rad1 Re8 16. Kh1 $14 {Caruana - Giri, Ekaterinburg, 2021. Regarding the c6-pawn, which controls the d5-square, Black can allow himself an exchange of one of the defenders of White's central pawn.}) 14. Rad1 (14. Bxg4 Nxg4 15. Kh1 Ne5 $11) (14. Kh1 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Re8 16. Rad1 Qb6 $11) 14... Bxe2 15. Nxe2 d5 $1 {An essential counterstrike.} ({The potential danger behind the manoeuvre Nd4-f5 should not be underestimated, therefore} 15... Qb6+ 16. Be3 {looks risky for the second player.}) 16. exd5 (16. e5 Ne4 {is double-edged, now} 17. Nd4 Qb6 18. Be3 {can be met by} Bg5 19. Bxg5 Nxg5 20. c4 Rad8 $11) ({Another idea behind 15...d5! is revealed after} 16. Ng3 Qb6+ {, when the trade of the bishops after} 17. Be3 Bc5 {is helpful again -} 18. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 19. Qd4 ({in case of} 19. Kh1 {White must reckon with} Ng4) 19... Qxd4+ 20. Rxd4 $11) 16... Nxd5 17. Bc1 (17. Be5 Qb6+ 18. Bd4 (18. Kh1 Bf6) 18... c5 19. Bf2 Nf6 $11) 17... Bg5 (17... Bf6 $11) 18. Nd4 Bxc1 19. Rxc1 Qb6 20. c4 Ne7 $11 *

