1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be2 Bb4 $1 ({Besides the usual Scheveningen, Black can go to the Taimanov with} 6... Qc7) (6... d5 {is strategically risky -} 7. exd5 exd5 8. a3 $14 {[%cal Gc1e3]}) 7. O-O {White's main weapon, based on speedy development.} (7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. O-O {may just transpose, Black has also} d5 $132 {at his disposal}) ({If White is not in the sacrificial mood, then he can opt for} 7. Qd3 O-O 8. O-O (8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5 Nd5 10. O-O d6 $11) 8... Ne5 (8... e5 $5) ({regarding the location of Qd3,} 8... d5 $5 {is more justified -} 9. exd5 exd5 10. Bf4 Re8 $132) 9. Qg3 d6 10. Rd1 ({in case of} 10. f4 $6 Ng6 {White has to find a decent way to protect his hanging central pawn}) ({clearly preferable is} 10. Bg5 Bd7 11. Rfd1 Rc8 {, when} 12. f4 Ng6 13. f5 Ne5 {can lead to a repetition like} 14. Bh6 Ne8 15. Bg5 Nf6 $11) 10... a6 $1 11. Bg5 (11. f4 $6 {is risky again, as demonstrated by} Ng6 12. Bf3 e5 $1 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Nf5 Qc7 $15) 11... Ng6 12. a3 Bxc3 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxc3 e5 $1 {A reasonable decision to modify the central pawn structure, as Nd4 is far away from the exposed d5-square. Black has good prospects, as shown by} 15. Nb3 Nf4 16. Bf1 Qg6 17. Kh1 Bd7 $11) 7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 Nxe4 9. Nxc6 {By far not the only attacking option:} (9. Ba3 $6 Nxc3 10. Nxc6 dxc6 11. Qe1 Nxe2+ 12. Qxe2 Qa5 13. Bd6 f6 $15 {[%cal Ge8f7]}) (9. Bd3 {is a major alternative, after} d5 {White can bring Bc1 to the desired a3-f8 diagonal at once or after trading a pair of minor pieces} 10. Nxc6 ({the immediate} 10. Ba3 {is more risky for White, after the best reply} Qa5 $1 {he needs miracles in order to keep the balance:} 11. Nb5 (11. Qc1 Nxc3 12. Nxc6 (12. Nb3 Qc7 13. Qe1 d4 14. f4 b6 $132) 12... bxc6 13. Bd6 f6 14. Qf4 Ne4 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 Qd5 $132) 11... a6 (11... Nxc3 $5 12. Nd6+ Kd7 13. Qc1 f6 14. Re1 b5 15. Nf7 Re8 16. Nd6 Rd8 $11) 12. Nd6+ Nxd6 13. Bxd6 Qd8 14. Ba3 Qa5 $11) (10. Bxe4 dxe4 11. Ba3 Nxd4 12. cxd4 {is neutralized by the same} Qa5 13. Bd6 $140 (13. Qc1 $6 Bd7) 13... Qd5 14. Ba3 {and Black can just repeat with} Qa5 $11) 10... bxc6 11. Ba3 c5 {is leading most of the ensuing lines to almost inevitable draws because of the remaining opposite-coloured bishops:} 12. Bxe4 (12. c4 O-O 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Bxe4 (14. c4 Bb7 $11) 14... dxe4 15. Bxc5 Re8 $11) (12. Re1 {is not a serious improvement either after the simple} O-O {e.g.} 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Bxc5 Re8 15. Rxe4 Bb7 16. Qxd8 Rexd8 17. Rb4 Bd5 $11) 12... dxe4 13. Bxc5 ({little is changed by} 13. Qxd8+ Kxd8) 13... Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 {and Black cannot castle, but he should hold with the help of the typical escape} f6 15. c4 Kf7 {, for example} 16. Rab1 Ba6 (16... e5 $5) 17. Rd7+ Kg6 18. Rb3 Rhd8 (18... Rhc8 $144) 19. Rg3+ Kf5 20. Rgxg7 h5 $11) (9. Bf3 d5 10. Bxe4 dxe4 {has already been analyzed to draw in the 9.Bd3 line}) (9. Qd3 {has to be considered again -} d5 10. Ba3 (10. Nxc6 $143 bxc6 11. Ba3 Qa5 12. Bb4 Qb6 $132 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 10... Ne7 ({worth trying is} 10... Qa5 $5 11. Nb5 $140 a6 12. Nd6+ Nxd6 13. Bxd6 {and only now} Ne7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Qd4 f6 $13) 11. c4 O-O 12. Bf3 (12. Rad1 Re8 {will probably transpose}) 12... Re8 13. Rad1 Ng5 $11) 9... dxc6 ({Of course not} 9... bxc6 $2 10. Qd4 $16) 10. Bd3 {The main move yields ample compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} ({Black must feel relieved without queens on the board after} 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bf3 Nf6 12. Rd1+ Bd7 {, though it is still early for him to relax, e.g.} 13. Bf4 (13. g4 h6) (13. c4 e5) (13. Rb1 Kc8) 13... Nd5 {and now:} 14. Bd6 {covers the d-file and} (14. Bg3 b5 $1 ({securing the proid centralized knight is much stronger than the greedy} 14... Nxc3 $6 15. Rd3 Nd5 16. c4 Nb6 17. Rb1 Kc8 18. Be2 $36) 15. a4 Ke7 $11) 14... Nxc3 15. Rd3 Nd5 {is more justified here:} 16. c4 (16. a4 Re8 $1 17. Rb3 (17. c4 e5 $1 {is a nice trick worth remembering!}) 17... b5 18. axb5 cxb5 19. Rba3 Rc8 20. Rxa7 Rxc2 $11) 16... Nb6 17. Rb1 (17. Rad1 Kc8 18. Bc5 Rd8 19. Be7 Re8 20. Bc5 Rd8 $11) 17... Kc8 18. Rb4 e5 19. Ra3 Be6 $1 20. Rxb6 $140 Kd7 {and the tactical skirmish is about to end in a repetition after} 21. Rxb7+ Kxd6 22. c5+ Kxc5 23. Rc3+ Kd4 24. Rxc6 Rab8 25. Rd6+ Kc5 26. Rc6+ $11) 10... Nc5 $1 {Black goes immediately after the annoying bishops.} ({Instead,} 10... Nf6 $6 {can provide the opponent with a long-term initiative, for example} 11. Re1 (11. Ba3 Qc7 12. Qf3 c5 13. Rab1 O-O 14. Rfe1 $36) 11... O-O 12. c4 $36) 11. Qg4 ({Black has prepared to meet} 11. Ba3 {with} Nxd3 12. cxd3 Qa5 13. Bb4 Qf5 {(otherwise Black will continue with 14....c5)} 14. d4 $140 f6 $132 {[%cal Ge8f7]}) 11... O-O $5 {A bit risky, though a perfectly playable option.} (11... Qf6 {is the main theoretical continuation, here are several important lines -} 12. Bg5 Qxc3 13. Rad1 (13. Qg3 {can finish in a beautiful draw by repetition after} Nxd3 14. Rad1 f6 15. Rxd3 Qc5 16. Rfd1 O-O 17. Bh6 Qe7 18. Rd8 b5 19. Bxg7 Qxg7 20. Rxf8+ Kxf8 21. Rd8+ Kf7 22. Qc7+ Kg6 23. Qg3+ $11) 13... h6 14. Be3 (14. Bd2 Qf6 15. Bb4 Nxd3 16. Rxd3 {looks dangerous, as Ke8 is stuck in the center, after} e5 17. Qc4 Bf5 18. Rdd1 Qe6 19. Qc3 f6 {, similarly to the line with 11.Ba3 from above, the king gets access to the f7-square, and Black has his chances in the long run, e.g.} 20. f4 e4 21. Rd6 Qc8 $132) (14. Bf4 Qf6 15. Qg3 Nxd3 16. Rxd3 O-O 17. Bd6 Rd8 18. Rd4 {is a clever way to create the threat 19.Be5, to which Black can obtain enough material for the queen after} Qxd4 19. Be5 Qxe5 20. Qxe5 Rd5 21. Qe2 b6 $44 {/=}) ({Black's task is easier in case of the insertion} 14. Qh3 Bd7 {before} 15. Bd2 Qf6 16. Bb4 {e.g.} b6 17. Bc4 e5 18. Qa3 Qe7 $132) (14. Qh5 b6 $132) 14... O-O 15. Bxh6 ({harmless is} 15. Bd4 e5 $1 16. Qxg7+ Kxg7 17. Bxc3 Re8 $11) 15... f5 16. Qg6 ({no better is} 16. Qg3 Ne4) ({or} 16. Qg5 b6) 16... Qf6 17. Qxf6 Rxf6 18. Bf4 (18. Bg5 Rf7 19. Be2 b6 $11) 18... b6 $1 ({premature is} 18... Nxd3 $6 19. Rxd3 e5 20. Bxe5 Rf7 21. Rd6 $14 {Huschenbeth - Ragger, Germany, 2021}) 19. Rfe1 Nxd3 20. Rxd3 Ba6 21. Rc3 Bb5 22. Bg5 Rff8 23. Rxe6 Rfe8 $11) 12. Ba3 {The most principled continuation.} ({Roughly equal is} 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Qxc5 Re8 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5]}) 12... e5 13. Qg3 (13. Qe2 Qe7 14. Rae1 Re8 {will transpose}) (13. Qh5 {dorces} g6 {, but Black should not be afraid of} 14. Qh6 b6 15. f4 {, for example} e4 16. Bxc5 bxc5 17. Bxe4 Qd2 18. Rf3 c4 $11) 13... Qe7 $1 $146 ({An essential refinement over} 13... b6 14. Bxc5 bxc5 15. Qxe5 Qd5 {So far V. Ivic - M. Perunovic, Bajina Basta, 2022, when White could improve by means of} 16. Qe7 $1 Bf5 17. c4 Qd7 18. Qxd7 Bxd7 19. Rfe1 Rfe8 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Rb1 Kf8 22. f3 $14 {with penetration along the b-file to come.}) 14. Rfe1 (14. Rae1 Re8 15. f4 e4 {os quite similar to the main text.}) 14... Re8 15. f4 (15. Qe3 b6 {is likely to transpose.}) 15... e4 16. Qe3 b6 17. Bxc5 {White can hardly delay this capture anymore.} Qxc5 18. Qxc5 bxc5 19. Bxe4 Bd7 20. Rad1 Rad8 {A critical position for assessing the whole variation - Black allows a small combination in return for sufficient counterplay in the ensuing rook ending.} 21. Bxh7+ (21. Bf3 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Kf8 23. Re5 ({here} 23. Rb1 {is not so frightening in the view of} g6 24. Rb7 Be6 25. Rxa7 Rd2 $11) 23... Be6 24. Rxc5 Bxa2 25. Rxc6 {and the most precise} Bd5 {will lead to full destruction of the queenside after} 26. Bxd5 Rxd5 $11) 21... Kxh7 22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. Rxd7 Re1+ 24. Kf2 Rc1 $1 25. Rxf7 (25. Rd2 Ra1 $11) 25... Rxc2+ 26. Kf1 Rc1+ $1 {The key resource - White's king must either leave the g2-pawn undefended or allow taking the one on c3 with a check.} (26... Rxa2 $2 27. Rf5 $18) 27. Ke2 Rc2+ 28. Kd3 Rxa2 (28... Rxg2 $2 29. Rxa7 Rxh2 30. a4 $18) 29. g4 Rxh2 $11 *

