{[%evp 0,50,24,31,46,46,46,46,46,46,46,26,26,5,5,1,1,23,77,69,32,32,32,27,53,53,79,68,111,35,62,59,47,29,57,32,32,32,51,51,51,51,104,97,108,-15,-67,-67,-67,-36,-6,-6,0]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bf4 $5 Bb4 $1 (6... d6 {is a reliable answer, especially for any devotee of the Sveshnikov -} 7. Nxc6 (7. Ndb5 e5 8. Bg5 {- B33}) 7... bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 {A similar position has been analyzed in Chapter 5 with 6.a3 Be7 included. Here Black has other bright tactical swindles up his sleeve -} 9. Nxd5 dxe5 $5 ({much more entertaining than} 9... cxd5 10. Bd3) 10. Bxe5 Qxd5 11. Bc3 Bb4 $1 {The big point of Black's play!} 12. Bxb4 (12. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 13. Qd2 Bxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Bb7 $11 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gc6c5]}) 12... Qe4+ 13. Qe2 Qxb4+ 14. c3 Qa4 $11) 7. Ndb5 {This interesting line is more often reached via 6.Ndb5 Bb4 7.Bf4!?} (7. e5 $6 Nd5 $132) (7. Nxc6 bxc6 {reinforces the opponent's center and White needs urgently to show something in return for it -} 8. Bd3 (8. Qd4 Qb6 9. O-O-O O-O 10. e5 Nd5 $132) 8... d5 9. e5 Nd7 10. O-O (10. Qg4 g6 11. O-O Be7 $132 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gh7h5]}) 10... O-O 11. Qf3 (11. Qg4 f5 $1 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Qg5 a5 $132 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) (11. Qh5 {is again met by} f5 {with a probable transposition}) 11... a5 12. Qh3 f5 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Be5 Ra7 15. a3 Bd6 16. Rae1 Raf7 $11) 7... Nxe4 8. Qf3 ({Yet another move order to the first critical position is} 8. Nc7+ Kf8 9. Qf3 (9. Nxa8 $2 Qf6 $19) 9... e5 (9... d5 {should also transpose}) 10. Nxa8 d5 {etc.}) 8... d5 9. Nc7+ ({For} 9. O-O-O Bxc3 10. Nc7+ Kf8 {see below.}) 9... Kf8 10. Nxa8 ({A minor alternative is} 10. O-O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 {and now:} e5 $1 (11... g5 $5 12. Qxe4 (12. Bg3 Rb8 13. Bb5 f5 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Nxd5 Rb7 $11) 12... Qxc7 13. Bxc7 dxe4 14. h4 g4 15. Bb5 (15. Bc4 f6) 15... f6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Rhe1 e5 18. Rxe4 Be6 19. Rb4 Kf7 $11) 12. Nxd5 f5 {is pretending for more:} 13. Be3 (13. Bc4 $2 exf4 14. Rhe1 Qg5 15. Nc7 g6 $19) (13. Bg3 h5 $1 (13... Qa5 $5 14. Bc4 Qc5 15. Bb3 (15. Qd3 Be6 $15) (15. Ne3 g6 $17) 15... a5 $1 16. a4 Qa3+ 17. Kb1 Nc5 $1 18. c4 Nxb3 19. Qxb3 Qxb3+ 20. cxb3 f4 21. Bh4 Rg8 (21... Bf5+ 22. Kb2 Kf7 $11) 22. f3 g5 23. Be1 g4 24. fxg4 Bxg4 $11) 14. Qe3 $1 (14. h3 $6 Be6 15. Bc4 {T. Sosa - M. Fromm, Sant Boi de Llobregat, 2023, when} Qg5+ $1 {looks strong,, e.g.} 16. Kb2 h4 17. Bh2 Bf7 $15) (14. h4 $2 Qa5 15. Bc4 Qc5 16. Bb3 a5 17. a4 Qa3+ 18. Kb1 Nc5 $17) 14... Qa5 15. f3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Be6 17. Bc4 Rd8 {and White must be happy to have} 18. Nb6 Kf7 19. Qg5 Qa3+ 20. Kb1 Ne7 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Qxh5+ Kf6 23. Qh4+ Kf7 $11) 13... Qa5 $1 14. Bc4 Be6 15. Bb3 Rd8 $1 16. c4 g6 (16... Kf7 $5 17. g4 Rhf8 18. Kb1 Kg8 19. gxf5 Bxf5 20. Qg2 Kh8 21. Rhg1 Bg6 $13) 17. g4 (17. Bh6+ Kf7 18. g4 Nd4 (18... Rhe8 19. Qe3 Nc5 20. Kb2 Bxd5 21. cxd5 Nxb3 22. axb3 Nb4 23. Ra1 Qc7 $132) 19. Rxd4 exd4 20. Qf4 Bxd5 21. cxd5 Qa3+ 22. Kb1 Qd6 23. Qf3 Rhe8 24. gxf5 Kg8 $132) {can be played at once, in comparison to 17.Bh6 from above Black can grab the given opportunity for} 17... Kg7 18. gxf5 Bxf5 19. Kb2 (19. Rhg1 Rhf8 20. Kb2 Rxd5 $1 21. Rxd5 Qc3+ 22. Kb1 Nd4 23. Qd1 Nxb3 24. axb3 Nxf2 $1 25. Bxf2 Qxb3+ $11) 19... Rxd5 $1 $146 (19... b5 $2 20. cxb5 Qxb5 {led to a draw in L. Dotzer- M. Kharitonov, Batumi, 2022, but} 21. Rhg1 $18 {would have had a crushing effect}) 20. Rxd5 (20. cxd5 $2 Qc3+ 21. Kb1 Nd4 $19) (20. Bh6+ $5 Kxh6 21. cxd5 Nd4 22. Qe3+ Kg7 23. f3 Nf6 24. Rxd4 (24. Qxe5 $6 Nc6 25. Qf4 Qb4 $15) 24... exd4 25. Qe7+ Kh6 26. Qxf6 Qc3+ 27. Kb1 {and here} Rc8 {forces White to go for a perpetual by} 28. Qh4+ $11) 20... Qc3+ 21. Kb1 (21. Ka3 Qb4+ $11) 21... Nd4 22. Qd1 (22. Rd7+ Kf6 $1) 22... Nxf2 $1 23. Bxf2 ({we have a myriad of perpetual fro both sides, the most beautiful of them seems to be} 23. Qe1 Bxc2+ 24. Bxc2 Qxc2+ 25. Ka1 Nd3 $1 26. Rd7+ $140 Kg8 27. Qd2 Qxd2 28. Bxd2 Nc2+ 29. Kb1 Na3+ $11) (23. Bxd4 exd4 24. Qe1 Ne4 25. Rd7+ Bxd7 26. Qxe4 Re8 27. Qxb7 Re1+ 28. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 29. Kb2 Qc3+ $11) 23... Nxb3 24. axb3 Qxb3+ 25. Ka1 Qa3+ $11) 10... e5 $1 11. Bd2 Nd4 12. Qd1 (12. Qd3 {has been tested at the highest level lately, including the most principled reply} Nc5 $1 (12... Kg8 $5 13. Rc1 h5 $13) 13. Qg3 Nxc2+ 14. Kd1 Nxa1 15. Qxe5 Ne4 $1 16. Be1 Bxc3 $1 (16... h5 $6 17. Qc7 $1 {has ultimately turned the tables in White's favour -} Ba5 18. Qxd8+ Bxd8 19. Nxd5 $14 {J. Van Foreest - F. Vallejo Pons, Linares, 2023}) (16... Bd6 $5 17. Qxd5 Nf6 18. Qd4 Qe7 19. Bc4 (19. Bd3 Bc5 20. Qf4 Bd6 21. Qc1 Be6 22. Nb5 Nd5 23. Bd2 Nb4 24. Bc4 Nbc2 25. Bd3 Nb4 $11) 19... Be5 20. Qxa7 g6 21. Bd2 Kg7 22. Re1 Rd8 23. Qa5 $1 Qd7 24. Nd5 Qg4+ 25. f3 Qxc4 26. Qxd8 Qc2+ 27. Ke2 Qc4+ 28. Kd1 (28. Kf2 $2 Bd4+ 29. Ne3 Qd3 $17) 28... Qc2+ $11) 17. bxc3 Qa5 $1 {is even better, with an eye on the "centralized" Kd1, for instance} 18. Bd3 f6 19. Qc7 Qa4+ {and the path diverges:} 20. Kc1 (20. Ke2 {is well met by quick mobilization of all the forces, namely} Bd7 $5 21. f3 Kf7 {[%cal Gh8c8]} 22. fxe4 Rc8 23. Qxb7 dxe4 24. Bb1 ({after} 24. Qd5+ Be6 25. Qxe4 Qxa2+ 26. Kf1 Nb3 $132 {White must look for a draw by repetition with} 27. Qb7+ Kg8 28. Qe4 Kf7 29. Qb7+) 24... Nc2 25. Bd2 Na3 26. Kf2 Nxb1 27. Rxb1 Qc6 {and Black regains the piece with interest -} 28. Qxc6 Bxc6 29. Nb6 axb6 30. Rxb6 $11) 20... Bd7 $1 21. f3 $1 (21. Kb2 $2 Kf7 $19 {[%cal Gh8c8]}) 21... Qa3+ (21... Ke7 $5 22. fxe4 Qxa2 23. Qc5+ Kd8 24. Qc7+ $11) 22. Kb1 Nc5 23. Bg3 Qxc3 24. Bd6+ Kf7 25. Bxc5 Qxd3+ 26. Kxa1 Qc3+ $11) 12... Qh4 $1 {In connection with the next move - Black's key to counterplay!} (12... Bg4 $2 13. Qc1 $16) 13. g3 Qf6 $1 14. Nxe4 ({Dubious is} 14. f4 $6 Qg6 $1 15. Bg2 $140 Bg4 {, for example} 16. Nxe4 Bxd1 17. Bxb4+ Kg8 18. Rxd1 Nxc2+ 19. Kf1 Qa6+ 20. Kg1 Nxb4 $17) 14... Nf3+ 15. Qxf3 {The only way to prolong the fight.} (15. Ke2 Nd4+ 16. Ke3 (16. Ke1 Nf3+ $11) 16... Nf5+ 17. Kf3 Nh4+ $11) 15... Qxf3 16. Bxb4+ Kg8 17. Nd6 Qxh1 18. O-O-O Be6 19. Nc7 (19. h4 $6 h5 20. Nc7 Qf3 $15) 19... Qxh2 20. Nxd5 {The main continuation.} (20. f4 $5 exf4 ({a rare battle of all the 4 minor pieces against a queen can be seen after} 20... h5 $5 21. f5 h4 22. fxe6 fxe6 23. gxh4 Qxh4 24. c4 Qe7 25. Ncb5 Rh1 26. Be2 Qg5+ 27. Bd2 Rxd1+ 28. Bxd1 Qg1 29. cxd5 exd5 30. Nc3 Kf8 $11) 21. Re1 fxg3 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. Rxe6 {is a sharp alternative, which seems to lead to a forced draw after} h5 24. Re8+ Kh7 25. Bd3+ g6 26. Re7+ Kg8 27. Bc3 Qg1+ 28. Kd2 Qf2+ $11) 20... Bxd5 21. Rxd5 Qxf2 22. Rd1 ({In reply to} 22. Bc4 {the subtle check} Qe3+ $1 {is designed to disrupt the harmony of White's army, forcing} 23. Kd1 (23. Rd2 $4 Qe1+ {Firouzja - Rapport, Paris, 2021}) 23... Qxg3 (23... h5 $5 {is playable, but who can resist creating such phalanx?}) 24. b3 (24. Bc3 Qg1+ 25. Kd2 Qg5+ $11) 24... h5 25. Kc1 (25. Nxf7 Qg4+ 26. Kc1 Kxf7 27. Rd4+ Kg6 28. Bd3+ Kf6 29. Rxg4 hxg4 $132) 25... h4 26. Rd3 Qg4 27. Nxf7 Qxc4 28. bxc4 Kxf7 29. Bc3 Ke6 30. Rh3 Rh5 31. Be1 g5 32. Kd1 Kf5 33. Ke2 Rh6 $44) (22. Rxe5 Qxf1+ 23. Re1 Qxe1+ 24. Bxe1 h5 $5 ({a possible improvement upon} 24... b6 25. Bc3 h5 26. Kd2 $11 {J. Swiatek - J. Dyson, FICGS email, 2021}) 25. Nxb7 g5 26. c4 h4 27. gxh4 gxh4 28. c5 h3 29. Bg3 h2 30. Bxh2 Rxh2 31. c6 Rh6 32. Nd8 Rh5 $11) 22... Qxg3 23. Bc4 h5 24. Bd2 ({One of the many exciting lines goes on with} 24. Bxf7+ Kh7 25. Bc4 Qg4 $1 {(a key move)} 26. Bd3+ g6 27. Ne4 Kg7 28. Be7 Rf8 $5 29. Bxf8+ $140 Kxf8 30. Kd2 h4 $11) (24. Rf1 {is played according to the principle that the threat is stronger than its execution, Black can disentangle his kingside by means of} Qg4 $1 25. Bc3 Rh6 $1 {with the forced sequence} 26. Rxf7 Qxc4 27. Rxg7+ Kxg7 28. Bxe5+ Kg6 29. Nxc4 Kf5 $132 {The smoke has finally cleared, the h-pawn is once again a big asset.}) 24... Qg4 $1 25. Bd5 Kh7 26. Nxf7 Rf8 27. Re1 $1 {White's best chance compared to:} (27. Ng5+ Kg6 28. Be4+ Rf5 {(in general Black is ready to invest material, especially for eliminating the light-squared bishop, in order to advance his kingside pawns)} 29. Be3 (29. Rf1 $2 Qxe4) 29... Kf6 30. Rd6+ Ke7 31. Bxf5 Qxf5 32. Rd1 h4 $11) (27. Rf1 $6 h4) 27... h4 ({Much simpler than} 27... Qd4 28. Be4+ Kg8 29. Nxe5 Rf1 $1 30. Rxf1 Qxe4 31. Nd3 Qg2 32. Re1 h4 33. Nf4 Qg3 34. Re3 Qg1+ 35. Re1 Qg3 36. Re3 Qg1+ 37. Re1 {1/2 Grandelius - Gelfand, Malmo, 2023.}) 28. Be4+ ({Absolutely the same is} 28. Nxe5 Qg3 29. Be4+ Kg8 30. Bd5+ $11) 28... Kg8 29. Nxe5 Qg3 {and it is time to call it a day -} 30. Bd5+ $11 ({Continuing with} 30. Bxb7 Rd8 {can bring trouble only to White.}) *

