1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Ndb5 Bb4 (6... d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {transposes to the Sveshnikov (B33).}) 7. a3 (7. Bf4 {has been explored in the previous Chapter.}) (7. e5 $5 Nxe5 8. Bf4 {is not an ordinary pawn sacrifice, after} d6 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Nxc3 O-O 11. Qd2 {the d6-pawn is a tempting target, so returning the material by} Nd5 $1 {deserves serious attention, for example} 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Qxd5 Qf6 $11 {and Black has already a slight lead in development}) (7. Nd6+ {is considered not dangerous after} Ke7 $1 {, as shown by:} 8. Nxc8+ (8. Bf4 e5 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bd2 Bxc3 $1 (10... d6 {is possible,}) ({but the shaky Nf5 requires from Black more resolute play like the break} 10... d5 {; the exchange of the text is actually preparing the most favourable conditions for it}) 11. bxc3 (11. Bxc3 d5 $1 {is the point}) 11... Nxe4 $1 12. Qg4 g6 $1 13. Bh6+ Kg8 14. Qxe4 d5 15. Rd1 Bxf5 16. Qxd5 Qxd5 17. Rxd5 Be6 18. Rd1 Nd8 $1 ({a necessary preparatory move, for} 18... f6 $4 {is falling into a nasty trap, namely} 19. Rd7 $3 $18) 19. f4 f6 20. fxe5 Nf7 $11) 8... Rxc8 9. Bd3 Re8 ({worth trying is} 9... d5 10. exd5 Ne5 $11 {, but the idea behind the text move to bring the last piece into play before any action is pretty sound}) 10. O-O ({after} 10. Bd2 Kf8 {Black is ready to strike at the center}) 10... Kf8 11. Bd2 (11. f4 {meets a very original reaction in} e5 $1 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 e4 $132 14. dxc6 $140 Rxc6 $5) 11... d5 12. exd5 exd5 ({continuing in the spirit of the featured branch of the 4 Knights Variation, though Black has the plausible alternative} 12... Nxd5 13. Bxh7 $140 Qa5 $11) 13. Re1 ({after both} 13. Bf5 Ra8) ({and} 13. a3 Ba5 {the thematic push d5-d4 is in the air}) 13... Rxe1+ 14. Bxe1 a6 $11) 7... Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 9. exd5 ({The other option} 9. Bd3 $5 {has been widely recommended in recent sources. The usual continuation is} dxe4 (9... O-O $6 10. O-O $14) 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 {, which is in general considered, given the pair of bishops, a slightly better endgame on two results. Black main reply is} Bd7 {and now the path diverges:} 13. Re1 (13. c3 f5 14. Bc2 e5 $11 {[%cal Ge8f7,Gd7e6]}) (13. b3 O-O-O 14. Bb2 Nd4 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 15. Kc1 (15. Bxd4 Bc6 16. Bxc6 Rxd4+ 17. Ke2 bxc6 18. Rhd1 Rd5 $11 {Shevchenko - Xu Xiangyi, Jerusalem, 2022}) 15... Bc6 16. Re1 Rhe8 17. Bc3 f6 $11) (13. a4 O-O-O 14. Bd2 (14. Ra3 {must be one of the ideas behind 13.a4, but Black is also able to succeed in his intention to trade the light-squared bishops, this time by means of} Nb4 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 15. Ke2 Bc6 16. Bxc6 Nxc6 $11) ({for} 14. Re1 {see E2) below.}) 14... Ne5 15. Kc1 ({indeed,} 15. Re1 {will be followed by the same} Bc6 $11) 15... Bc6 16. Re1 Rd4 17. Bxc6 Nxc6 18. Be3 Rd5 19. c3 Rhd8 $11) (13. Be3 {requires a different approach from Black, namely} f5 $1 (13... O-O-O 14. Kc1 $14 {would justify White's opening strategy}) 14. Bd3 (14. Bf3 e5 15. Kc1 Rc8 16. g3 (16. Re1 Kf7 17. g3 Be6 $11) 16... Na5 $1 17. Kb1 Bc6 18. Bxc6+ Nxc6 $11) 14... Ne5 (14... e5 15. Kc1) (14... Kf7 $5) 15. Be2 Ng4 16. Bd4 Bc6 17. Ke1 e5 18. Bc3 O-O-O 19. Rg1 ({no better is} 19. f3 Ne3 20. Kf2 Nxc2 21. Rad1 Nd4) 19... Rhe8 (19... Nxh2 $5 20. f3 e4) 20. Rd1 Rxd1+ 21. Bxd1 {and Sanal - Mamedyarov, Playchess.com INT, 2020, could continue with} g5 22. Be2 Nf6 $11) 13... O-O-O 14. Bd2 (14. Be3 Nd4 $1 15. Bd3 (15. Kc1 Bc6 16. Bxc6 Nxc6 $11) 15... Bc6 (15... Bb5 $5) 16. f3 Nb3 (16... Bb5 $5 17. Bxb5 Nxb5+ 18. Kc1 Nd4 $11) 17. Rb1 Bb5 18. Bxa7 Rxd3+ 19. cxd3 Bxd3 20. Re3 Bxb1 21. Rc3+ Kd7 22. Rxb3 Kc6 23. Ke2 Ba2 24. Rc3+ Kd7 25. b3 Rc8 $11 {Kramnik - Rapport, Paris, 2021}) (14. a4 $5 Nb4 $5 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 15. Bg5 (15. Bd2 Bc6 16. Kc1 Rd4 17. Bxc6 Nxc6 $11) (15. Kd2 Bc6+ 16. Kc3 a5 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. b3 Rd5 $132) 15... f6 16. Bd2 Bc6 17. Kc1 Rd4 18. Bxc6 Nxc6 19. Rxe6 Ne5 20. Bc3 (20. Be3 Rh4 21. Bxa7 Rxh2 $11) 20... Rg4 $1 {The point of the pawn sacrifice - with Re6 under the threat of being trapped, White does not have time to save his important g2-pawn.} 21. Bxe5 fxe5 22. Ra3 Rxg2 23. Re7 Rg1+ 24. Kd2 Rf8 25. Rc3+ (25. Ke2 Rg2 26. Rf3 Rxf3 27. Kxf3 Rxh2 28. Rxg7 Rh1 $11) 25... Kd8 26. Rxb7 Rxf2+ 27. Kd3 Rf3+ 28. Kc4 Rg4+ 29. Kb3 Rxc3+ 30. Kxc3 (30. bxc3 e4) 30... Rxa4 31. Rxg7 Rh4 $11) 14... Nd4 15. a4 Bc6 16. Ra3 Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Rd5 18. Rd3 {White has achieved a good version of the line with 13.a4, but it is still difficult for him to claim any advantage, for example} Rhd8 19. Bc3 (19. Be3 Nc6 20. Rxd5 Rxd5+ 21. Ke2 a6 22. b4 b5 23. c4 bxc4 24. Rxc4 Kd7 $11) 19... Nc6 20. Bxg7 Rxd3+ 21. cxd3 Rg8 $1 (21... Rxd3+ 22. Ke2 $14) 22. Rg4 Ne5 23. Rg3 Nxd3 $11) (9. Bb5 O-O $11) 9... exd5 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O (11. h3 {is wasting time for stopping ....Bg4, Black is very active after} Re8+ 12. Ne2 Ne4 13. O-O (13. Bxe4 Rxe4 14. O-O d4 15. b4 Re8 $11) 13... Bf5 14. c3 Qh4 15. Bf4 Rad8 $11) 11... Bg4 $1 {The trendy move.} ({Besides,} 11... d4 {has been considered the main reply for long.}) 12. f3 {Exposing the a7-g1 diagonal, but the alternatives are not helpful for the mobilization, here they are in brief:} (12. Qd2 Re8 (12... d4 $5 13. Ne2 Re8 14. Ng3 Ne5 15. b3 {brought success in Indjic - Abdusattorov, chess.com INT, 2021, but Black could have played the promising} h5 $132) 13. h3 (13. Qf4 Bh5) 13... Bh5 14. Re1 Qd7 $11) ({harmless is} 12. Be2 Bxe2 13. Nxe2 d4 (13... Re8 $11) 14. Qd3 (14. Bg5 h6 15. Bh4 Re8 16. Qd3 g5 17. Bg3 Qb6 $11) 14... Qd5 $11) (12. Ne2 {can be answered with the natural} Re8 ({an interesting alternative is} 12... Qb6 $5 13. h3 $140 Bh5 14. b4 Rfe8 15. Re1 Rad8 {and Black is fully mobilized and has every chance to take over the initiative after} 16. Bg5 Nd4 $11) 13. h3 (13. f3 Bh5 14. Nf4 Bg6 15. Nxg6 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 hxg6 17. b3 Ne5 (17... d4 $5) 18. Be2 {So far Areshchenko - Shankland, Krasnaya Polyana, 2021, here} d4 {is worth of attention again, for instance} 19. Bb2 Rad8 $132) 13... Bxe2 (13... Bh5 {is good enough, but Black can also gain tempi for his development}) 14. Bxe2 Qb6 15. Bd3 Ne4 16. b4 Ne5 $11) 12... Bh5 13. Bg5 {This sally is leaving the b2-pawn undefended.} (13. Kh1 {avoids that queen check, but White is obviously behind in his mobilization -} d4 14. Ne2 (14. Ne4 $6 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bg6 $15 {can turn even worse for him with the exchange of his best minor pieces}) 14... Qb6 15. Nf4 Bg6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 {with almost full transposition to the aforementioned Areshchenko - Shankland.} 17. Re1 Rfe8 $11) ({Very similar to the latter are also} 13. Ne2 Qb6+ 14. Kh1 Bg6 $11) ({and} 13. Re1 d4 14. Ne2 Qb6 15. Nf4 (15. Bg5 Nd5 16. Nf4 Nxf4 17. Bxf4 Bg6 $11) 15... Bg6 {, here White can at least save a tempo on playing Kg1-h1.}) 13... Qb6+ {As said, this is the most principled continuation.} (13... Bg6 $6 14. Rf2 $14) 14. Kh1 {It is hard to say whether avoiding the pin is better than the two options.} (14. Rf2 $5 Ne4 $1 15. Nxe4 (15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxb2 17. c4 Qe5 18. Re2 Qd4+ 19. Qxd4 Nxd4 20. Rb2 b6 $11) 15... dxe4 16. Bxe4 Qxb2 {is forced and now:} 17. Bd5 $5 $146 {may transpose after} (17. Qc1 Qxc1+ (17... Qc3 {is possible, it is hard to recommend anything else than} 18. Bd2 Qc5 19. Be3 Qe5 $11) 18. Rxc1 f6 19. Bf4 (19. Be3 Bg6 $11) 19... Bg6 20. Bd5+ Bf7 21. c4 Rac8 $11 {Carlsen - Artemiev, chess24.com INT, 2021}) ({sharper is} 17. g4 Bg6 18. Bd5 Qc3 (18... h6 $5 19. c4 Qb6 20. Bf4 Ne7) 19. f4 (19. h4 h6 20. h5 Bh7 {has not achieved much - the location of his preserved Bd5 is still very shaky, as proved by} 21. Bd2 Qc5 22. c4 Rad8 23. Kg2 b5 $11) (19. Rb1 h6 20. Bh4 (20. Bd2 Qc5) (20. Bf4 Rfd8 21. Rxb7 Rac8 22. Rd2 Re8 $44) 20... Nd4 (20... Rae8 $5) 21. Rxb7 Nxc2 22. Qd2 Rac8 $11) 19... h6 20. Bh4 (20. f5 $6 Bxf5 21. Bd2 Qd4) 20... Kh8 21. f5 {looks more dangerous, but after} Bh7 22. Rf3 (22. f6 $2 g5 $17) (22. Rb1 f6 $15) 22... Qc5+ 23. Bf2 Qd6 24. Be4 (24. Rd3 Ne5) 24... Qc7 25. Qd2 Rae8 26. Re1 f6 $11 {Black has consolidated - his queen is now in safety and Bh7 is ready to enter the game again}) (17. Rb1 Qxa3 18. Rxb7 Qa6 (18... Rac8 $5) 19. Rd7 (19. Rc7 Rac8) 19... Bg6 20. Qd5 Rac8 21. Rd6 (21. h4 Nb8 22. Rd6 Qa1+ 23. Rf1 Qc3 24. h5 Rc5 25. hxg6 Rxd5 26. gxf7+ Rxf7 27. Rxd5 Nd7 28. Rd3 Qe5 $11) 21... Bxe4 22. fxe4 Qa1+ 23. Rf1 Qc3 24. Bd2 Ne7 25. Bxc3 Nxd5 {and the game Xu Yi - Xu Xiangyi, Nanjing, 2023, quickly petered out to a draw -} 26. Bxg7 Kxg7 27. exd5 Rxc2 $11) 17... Bg6 (17... Qe5 18. Bh4) 18. c4 ({indeed, in this situation White does not need the g2-g4 thrust, he can also try} 18. Rb1 Qxa3 19. Rxb7 Rac8 20. c4 h6 21. Bf4 Rfd8 $11) 18... Qb6 19. Raa2 (19. Qd2 Rfe8) 19... Rfe8 (19... Rac8 20. Rab2 Qc7) 20. Rab2 Qc5 21. Rb5 ({Black, similarly to the main text, should easily hold after} 21. Rxb7 Rab8 22. Bxc6 Qxc6 23. Rxb8 Rxb8 24. Qd5 Qxd5 25. cxd5 Rb1+ 26. Rf1 Rxf1+ 27. Kxf1 f6 $11) 21... Qxa3 22. Rxb7 Rac8 23. f4 h6 24. f5 (24. Bh4 Na5 25. f5 (25. Rxa7 Qc5 26. Rd7 Nxc4 $11) 25... Bh5 $1 26. Qxh5 Re1+ 27. Rf1 Rxf1+ 28. Kxf1 Qd3+ 29. Kf2 (29. Qe2 $2 Qxf5+) 29... Qd2+ $11) (24. h4 Qc3 25. Qg4 (25. f5 $5 Re1+ $140 26. Qxe1 Qxe1+ 27. Rf1 Qe5 28. fxg6 {is a very resourceful try, but after} Qd4+ 29. Rf2 hxg5 30. Rbxf7 Kh8 31. Bxc6 {the own king cannot hide from the checks -} Qd1+ 32. Rf1 Qd4+ $11) 25... Qe1+ 26. Rf1 Qe3+ 27. Kh2 (27. Kh1 $144 Qe2) 27... Qe2 28. Qxe2 Rxe2 29. Bf3 (29. f5 Bh5) 29... Ra2 30. f5 Bxf5 31. Bxc6 Rxc6 32. Rxf5 hxg5 33. Rfxf7 Rxc4 $11) (24. Rf1 Qc5+ 25. Kh1 Qd4 $11) 24... Bh5 $1 {This familiar deflection motif is saving the day again.} 25. g4 (25. Bc1 Qa6 26. Qxh5 Qxb7 27. Bd2 Re5 $132) 25... hxg5 26. gxh5 Ne7 {Well played - instead of placing the knight on an attractive central square, Black is getting rid of the other bishop.} 27. Bxf7+ $5 (27. f6 Nxd5 28. Qxd5 Qc1+ 29. Kg2 Qxc4 30. Qxc4 Rxc4 31. fxg7 {Black has managed to simplify and here} Rf4 $1 {leads to a forced draw -} 32. Rxf4 gxf4 33. h6 Kh7 $1 34. Rxf7 Kxh6 35. Kf3 {(alas, 35.Rf8 does not work)} Rg8 36. Rxa7 Rxg7 $11) 27... Kxf7 28. h6 (28. f6 gxf6 29. Qd5+ Kg7 30. Qe4 Qa1+ 31. Kg2 Qe5 32. Qg6+ Kh8 33. Qh6+ Kg8 34. Rxf6 Qe2+ $11) 28... Red8 29. Qh5+ Kg8 30. Qxg5 (30. hxg7 {is another serious winning try, to which Black has to find the only, but sufficient queen transfer} Qa1+ $1 31. Kg2 Qf6 32. Qh8+ Kf7 33. Qh5+ $11) 30... Qa1+ 31. Kg2 Qf6 32. Qxf6 gxf6 33. Rxe7 Rxc4 $11) 14... Ne4 $1 15. Nxe4 (15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxb2 $11) (15. Bh4 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Qc5 $11) 15... dxe4 16. Bxe4 Qxb2 17. Qb1 (17. Re1 Rae8 (17... Bg6) 18. Qb1 (18. Qd6 Bg6) 18... Qxb1 {An adequate reaction - as Ra8 has left its corner Qb2-b6 is less effective, but Black can use the extra move after} 19. Rexb1 Bg6 20. Bxg6 hxg6 21. Rxb7 f6 22. Bf4 {with penetrating on the penultimate rank -} Re2 $44 {/=}) (17. Qd6 {protects the a3-pawn, thus helping White to win a pawn after} Bg6 18. Rab1 Qc3 19. Rxb7 Bxe4 20. fxe4 {, although the latter is blockaded by} Qc4 21. Qd3 Ne5 22. Qxc4 Nxc4 $11 {Black will srill need to trade a pair of rooks (preferably the active Rb7) in order to exploit the vulnerability of the opponent's isolated pawns.}) ({We have already seen of} 17. Bd5 Bg6 {, when investigating the deviation with 14.Rf2. The big difference here is apparently the hanging c2-pawn, so:} 18. Ra2 (18. Rb1 Qxa3 19. Rxb7 h6 $5 (19... Qa6 {, keeping an eye on Rf1 as well, can be played immediately}) 20. Bh4 (20. Bxh6 Rad8 21. Bg5 Bxc2 22. Qxc2 Rxd5 23. Qxc6 Rxg5 $11) 20... Qa6 21. Rb2 Rab8 22. Ra2 Qc8 $11) 18... Qc3 19. Bd2 Qd4 20. Bb4 Qxd1 21. Rxd1 Rfe8 22. c4 {White has skillfully pressed on the queenside, but the short maneuver} Bf5 23. g4 Be6 {seems to neutralize gradually the annoying Bd5 and the initiative respectively, for instance} 24. Bc3 Rad8 25. Rad2 Bxd5 26. cxd5 Ne5 27. d6 f6 $11) (17. Rb1 Qxa3 18. Rxb7 Qa6 19. Rc7 (19. Rb1 Bg6 {is similar to 18.Rb1 Qxa3 from above -} 20. Ra1 Qb6 $11) 19... Rac8 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Re1 Bg6 $11) 17... Qb6 $1 (17... Qxb1 $143 18. Rfxb1 Bg6 19. Bxg6 (19. Bd5 Nd8) 19... hxg6 20. Rxb7 Rfc8 $14) 18. Qxb6 (18. c4 Bg6 19. Qxb6 axb6 20. Bd5 Ra4 21. Rfe1 h6 22. Be7 Rc8 23. Bd6 Na5 $11) 18... axb6 19. Rfb1 (19. Be3 Bg6 20. Bd5 Bxc2 21. Rfc1 Bf5 22. Bxb6 Ra6 $11) 19... Bg6 20. Bxc6 {There is a certain logic behind trading the bishops:} (20. Rxb6 Bxe4 21. fxe4 f6 (21... Na5 $5 {Rf8-c8-c4}) 22. Be3 Rf7 $11) (20. Bxg6 hxg6 21. Rxb6 Nd4 $5 (21... Rfe8) (21... Na5 $5) 22. c3 (22. Rxb7 Nxc2 $11) 22... Nc2 23. Rc1 Rfe8 24. h4 $5 (24. Rxb7 Rxa3 25. Rb2 Re1+ 26. Rxe1 Nxe1 27. h4 Nd3 28. Rb8+ Kh7 29. Rb7 Kg8 $11) (24. h3 Nxa3 25. Rxb7 f6 26. Bf4 g5 27. Bg3 Nc4 $44) (24. Kg1 {might be White's best bet, to which the game will probably take the same course as after 24.h3}) 24... Ne1 $1 {An incredible resource - suddenly Bg5 is in danger:} 25. Rd1 (25. Rxb7 Nd3 (25... f6 26. Bd2 Nd3 {Re2 seems to yield Black great compensation}) 26. Rcb1 f6 27. Rc7 fxg5 28. Rbb7 gxh4 29. Rxg7+ $11) 25... Rxa3 26. Rbb1 Nc2 27. Rxb7 Rxc3 28. Rdd7 Rf8 29. Be7 Re8 30. Bd8 (30. Bd6 Rd3) 30... Ne3 31. Rxf7 Rxd8 32. Rxg7+ Kh8 $11) (20. Bd3 Bxd3 21. cxd3 Ra6 22. Be3 Rfa8 $1 23. Rxb6 $140 Rxa3 24. Rxa3 Rxa3 25. Rxb7 {and the cool-blooded} f6 {fixes an inevitable draw -} 26. h3 Rxd3 $11) 20... bxc6 21. Rxb6 h6 ({Little is changed by the immediate} 21... Bxc2 22. Rxc6 Ba4 23. Rc7 (23. Rb6 f6) 23... Rfc8 24. Rac1 Rxc7 25. Rxc7 h6 26. Be7 Ra6 $11 {Shomoev - Chigaev, Sochi, 2022. The following two examples from the games of Nepomniachtchi are like tweens of this game; the verdict in all of them remains one and the same - the opposite-colored bishops are nullifying White's extra pawn.}) 22. Bf4 (22. Be7 Rfe8 23. Bb4 {Nepomniachtchi - Rapport, Paris, 2021} Bxc2 24. Rxc6 Rac8 $11) 22... Bxc2 23. Rxc6 Rfc8 24. Bc7 Ba4 25. Rc3 f6 26. h4 h5 27. Kh2 Kf7 $11 {Nepomniachtchi - Caruana, Saint Louis, 2022.} *

