1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 (7. Bd3 {, but with Nb1-d2 and eventual c2-c4 has already been analyzed in the first Chapters.} d5 {is possible again -} 8. O-O Be7 9. Re1 (9. Qf3 O-O 10. Qg3 Nd7 11. Bh6 Bf6 $11 {[%cal Gg8h8]}) (9. Qe2 O-O 10. Bf4 a5 $11) 9... O-O 10. Qe2 ({as we already know, an impetuous kingside action like} 10. e5 Nd7 11. Qh5 $6 {is parried by the resolute} f5 $15) 10... a5 (10... Re8 $5) 11. e5 (11. Bg5 a4) 11... Nd7 12. Na4 c5 13. c4 {and here even} dxc4 $5 14. Bxc4 (14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qe4+ Kg8 16. Qxa8 Nxe5 $1 17. Bg5 $1 Nd3 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Re3 Bb7 20. Qa7 (20. Qxa5 $2 Qf6 $17) 20... Rd8 $44) 14... Nb6 {(Black can also rely on this jump on the previous move)} 15. Rd1 Qc7 16. Nxb6 Qxb6 17. a4 (17. Bd2 a4) 17... Bb7 18. Bd2 Rfd8 19. Bc3 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Qc6 21. f4 Rd8 $1 (21... Qxa4 $2 22. f5 $16) 22. Rxd8+ Bxd8 $11) 7... Nd5 8. Ne4 (8. Nxd5 $6 cxd5 9. Bd3 Qc7 (9... Ba6 $11) 10. Qe2 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 Bc5 $132) 8... Qc7 {The main move, it is useful to elicit the f-pawn to the 4th rank in advance.} ({The most important alternative is} 8... Bb7) 9. f4 Qb6 10. a3 $5 {This move and 10.Bd3 (see below) are the major alternatives of 10.c4:} (10. Bd3 f5 $1 ({a dynamic approach;} 10... Ba6 {is the main theoretical move -} 11. Bxa6 Qxa6 12. Qe2 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2 f5 14. Nf2 c5 {is about equal}) 11. exf6 gxf6 {and now:} 12. f5 (12. c4 $6 Bb4+ 13. Ke2 f5 $15) ({Black must not be afraid of} 12. Qh5+ Kd8 13. Qe2 Rg8 14. a3 $140 h6 $5 {[%cal Gf6f5]} 15. c4 f5 16. Ng3 Nf6 17. Be3 Bc5 18. Bxc5 Qxc5 19. O-O-O Ng4 20. Rd2 Kc7 $132) (12. Bd2 f5 13. Ng5 (13. Qh5+ Kd8 14. Ng5 Kc7 $132) 13... Bg7 ({it is interesting to check} 13... Bc5 $5 {, thus securing the e7-square for the king}) 14. Qh5+ (14. c4 Nf6 15. Qe2 O-O 16. Bc3 d5 17. Nf3 c5 $132) 14... Kd8 15. Nf7+ Kc7 16. Nxh8 Bxh8 $44 {is of great significance for the general understanding of these irrational positions:} 17. Qe2 (17. Rb1 c5 18. c3 Bb7 $44) (17. c4 Nb4 18. Qe2 Ba6 19. Bc3 Bxc3+ 20. bxc3 Nxd3+ 21. Qxd3 d5 22. Qd4 (22. Rb1 Bxc4) 22... Bxc4 23. Qg7+ Kd6 24. Qe5+ $11) 17... Qxb2 18. O-O Qb6+ 19. Kh1 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 c5 $132) (12. a3 $6 f5 13. Ng5 Bg7 14. c4 ({it is essential that Black has once again huge compensation for the sacrificed exchange after} 14. Qh5+ Kd8 15. Nf7+ Kc7 16. Nxh8 Bxh8 {, as witnessed by} 17. Qe2 Nc3 $1 18. Qf2 Bd4 $15) 14... Nf6 15. Qe2 O-O $15) 12... exf5 {is opening a new page:} 13. Nf2 (13. Qh5+ Kd8 14. Qxf5 Bb4+ 15. c3 Re8 $1 16. Kd1 (16. cxb4 $143 Qd4 $1 $36) (16. Bd2 Bd6 17. O-O-O Rb8 18. b3 Be5) 16... Re5 17. Qf3 Be7 $132) 13... Ba6 $1 14. O-O ({White should castle after} 14. Qe2+ Kd8 {, because} 15. Bxa6 $2 {is falling into} Bb4+ 16. Kd1 Re8 $19) 14... Bxd3 (14... O-O-O $5) 15. Qxd3 O-O-O 16. Qxf5 Re8 $1 17. c4 Ne3 18. Bxe3 Qxe3 19. Rad1 Re6 $11) (10. Qe2 {covers the vulnerable e3-square, but it looks artificial and Black can benefit from that by} a5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 11. c4 Ba6 12. a3 Qd4 {[%cal Gd5b6]} 13. Rb1 f5 $1 {with rich play for Black -} 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 (15... Qxf6 $11) 16. Be3 Qe4 $132) (10. Qf3 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 11. a3 c5 12. Be2 Be7 $132) (10. c4 {is the subject of the final two Chapters.}) 10... Ne3 $5 {A straightforward idea to eliminate Bf1. Known alternatives are} (10... a5) ({and} 10... f5) 11. Qd3 (11. Qd2 Nxf1 12. Rxf1 c5 $132) 11... Nxf1 12. Rxf1 Ba6 13. c4 f5 $1 14. exf6 (14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. exd6 {reaches a middlegame with all the heavy pieces on the board and drawish tendencies because of the opposite-colored bishops.} c5 16. Rf3 {[%cal Gf3g3]} (16. Rf2 $143 Bb7 17. Be3 a5 $132 {Suleymanli - Gavrilescu, Chess.com INT, 2024}) 16... Bb7 17. Rg3 Rg8 {and White has to define the queenside pawn structure:} 18. b3 (18. a4 {[%cal Ga1a3]} Be4 19. Qd1 g6 ({Black can confidently play} 19... a5 {at once, for} 20. Qh5+ $6 g6 21. Qxh7 {is a risky affair -} O-O-O $36) 20. b3 ({the intended} 20. Raa3 {can be discouraged by} Qb4+ $140 21. Rac3 a5 $11) 20... a5 21. Bb2 O-O-O 22. Qd2 Kb7 {and the a5-pawn will be effortlessly defended, the position is rock-solid}) 18... Be4 19. Qd1 {may radically change the character of the position after} O-O-O 20. b4 (20. Be3 g5 $1 21. Rxg5 Rxg5 22. fxg5 f4 $1 23. Bf2 (23. Bxf4 Rf8 24. g3 e5 25. Be3 Rf3 $132) 23... Rg8 24. h4 h6 25. gxh6 Rxg2 26. Qh5 (26. Qe2 Qc6) 26... Kb7 27. h7 (27. Qxc5 Qxc5 28. Bxc5 Rh2 29. Bd4 Rxh4 30. Bg7 $11) 27... Rh2 $1 28. h8=Q Rh1+ 29. Kd2 Qxd6+ 30. Bd4 Rh2+ 31. Kc1 Rh1+ $11) 20... g5 $1 21. fxg5 Rdf8 (21... e5 22. Rb3 Rg6 23. Be3 Rxd6 24. Qe2 Qb7 25. Bxc5 Rc6 $44) 22. bxc5 (22. Rb3 f4 $132) 22... Qxc5 23. Be3 Qe5 24. Qd4 Qxd4 25. Bxd4 e5 $1 26. Bxa7 (26. Bxe5 f4 27. Rb3 Rxg5 28. Bd4 Re8 $11) 26... Kb7 27. Bf2 Kc6 28. Rb3 Rb8 29. Rxb8 Rxb8 30. a4 Bxg2 31. a5 Kxd6 32. a6 f4 33. a7 Rc8 $11) 14... d5 15. f7+ {An obliging decision - by depriving Ke8 of castling rights, White has taken responsibility to finish the attack against it.} ({In case of} 15. Be3 Bxc4 $1 16. Qc3 (16. Qd2 c5 $132) {Black's safest solution is to trade queens by} 16... Qb3 17. Qxb3 $140 Bxb3 18. f7+ Kxf7 19. Ng5+ Kg8 20. Rc1 (20. Nxe6 Re8 21. f5 c5 $11) 20... Bc4 21. Rf2 Re8 22. Nf3 Bd6 $11) ({The immediate} 15. Qc3 {reaches by force another complex middlegame with opposite-coloured bishops -} O-O-O 16. fxg7 Bxg7 17. Qxg7 dxe4 18. Qc3 Rhg8 $1 19. Be3 Qb7 20. Rd1 Rxd1+ 21. Kxd1 Rd8+ 22. Kc1 Rd3 {with plenty of activity, after} 23. Qh8+ Rd8 {it makes sense to repeat, while the game is also about equal after} 24. Qe5 Bxc4 $11) ({Yet another uncompromising possibility like} 15. Ng5 gxf6 16. Nxe6 Bxc4 17. Qf5 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 {seems to yield great compensation for the exchange, so it is sensible to look for a repetition of moves by means of} Qb5+ 19. Ke1 Qb6 $11) 15... Kxf7 16. f5 h6 $1 (16... Bxc4 {is supposedly good enough, but risky, for the king will have to return to its initial square -} 17. fxe6+ Ke8 {Here is some food for thought:} 18. Qf3 $1 {is the critical retreat -} (18. Qc3 Bxf1 19. Nd6+ Kd8 $1 20. Nf7+ (20. Qe5 Be7 21. Bg5 $11) 20... Kc7 21. Kxf1 Qb5+ 22. Ke1 Rg8 23. Qe5+ Kb6 24. Be3+ d4 $1 25. Qxd4+ (25. Bxd4+ Kb7) 25... Bc5 26. Qe5 Bxe3 27. Qxe3+ Qc5 28. Qb3+ Kc7 $140 29. Qg3+ Kb6 30. Qb3+ $11) 18... Qc7 $8 {and now:} 19. Bf4 (19. Qh5+ g6 20. Nf6+ Kd8 21. Qg5 h6 22. Ng8+ Kc8 $8 23. Rxf8+ Kb7 24. Qf6 Rxf8 25. Qxf8 Qe5+ 26. Kf2 $8 (26. Kd2 $4 d4 $19) 26... Rxg8 27. Qxg8 Qe2+ 28. Kg3 Qd3+ 29. Kh4 Qe4+ $11) 19... dxe4 20. Qc3 $1 Bd6 21. Bxd6 Qxd6 22. Qxg7 $1 (22. Qxc4 Rd8 23. Rf7 e3 $132 {/=}) 22... Bxf1 23. Qxh8+ Qf8 24. Qxf8+ ({perhaps White should better enter a rook ending after} 24. Qxh7 $1 Rd8) 24... Kxf8 25. Kxf1 a5 $11 {[%cal Ga8b8]}) 17. Be3 {The alternatives seem to result in forced draws, as follows:} (17. fxe6+ Kg8 18. Be3 (18. Ng3 Bxc4 19. Qg6 Bxf1 20. Nh5 Qd4 {(8)} 21. Qf7+ Kh7 22. Qf5+ $11) (18. Nf6+ gxf6 19. Qg6+ Bg7 20. Rxf6 Qg1+ $1 21. Rf1 Qd4 22. Qf7+ Kh7 23. Qf5+ $11) 18... dxe4 19. Qxe4 Qa5+ 20. Bd2 Qc5 21. b3 Rd8 22. Bb4 Qg5 23. Rxf8+ Rxf8 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Rd1 Bc8 $1 26. Qf3+ (26. Rd6 {should not change the expected result -} Qc1+ 27. Ke2 Qb2+ $11 28. Ke1 $140 Qc3+ 29. Ke2 Qb2+ {and Ke2 must stay away from the f-file because of ....Ke7}) 26... Kg8 27. Rd8+ $1 $11 Qxd8 $140 28. Qf7+ Kh7 29. Qf5+) (17. Qg3 {is the most direct road to perpetual -} dxe4 18. Qg6+ Kg8 19. Qxe6+ Kh7 20. Qg6+ Kg8 21. Qe6+ Kh7 22. Qg6+ {1/2 Balajayeva - Ohanyan, Doha, 2023.}) 17... Qa5+ $1 ({The capture} 17... Bxc4 {is once again by no means obligatory; its assessment depends on the wild complications after} 18. fxe6+ Kg6 19. Qc3 Qb5 20. Rf6+ Kh7 $13 {The initial impression is that White has at least a draw by perpetual in his pocket.}) 18. Bd2 ({Only Black can be better after} 18. b4 Bxb4+ 19. Kf2 dxe4 20. Qd7+ Be7 21. fxe6+ Kg6 {, for instance} 22. Qxe7 Bxc4 23. Rfd1 Rhe8 $132) 18... Qc7 $1 19. fxe6+ (19. Bc3 {allows} exf5 20. Rxf5+ Kg8 {with every chance to repel White's initiative, e.g.} 21. O-O-O Bxc4 22. Qh3 Re8 $132) 19... Kg8 20. Bc3 {Here too, White has a large choice:} (20. Qg3 Qxg3+ 21. Nxg3 Bxc4 22. Rf7 Re8 23. O-O-O Rxe6 24. Rxa7 g6 $11) (20. Qd4 dxe4 21. Qxe4 Re8 22. O-O-O Qe7 23. Rde1 Bc8 $1 24. Qxc6 Bxe6 {leads to a draw by force after} 25. Rxf8+ Qxf8 26. Rxe6 Qf1+ 27. Be1 Qf4+ 28. Bd2 Qf1+ $11) (20. Rf4 {is setting a trap, Black's best answer is} Bxc4 $1 ({dangerous is} 20... dxe4 $6 21. Qxe4 Re8 22. O-O-O $40 {the familiar sequence reveals the difference in the location of Rf1} Qe7 23. Re1 Bc8 24. Qxc6 Bxe6 {, when the game will be decided by the possible doubling of the rooks} 25. Rfe4 Qf7 26. Rxe6 $18) 21. Qc2 Rb8 (21... Ba6 $5 22. O-O-O dxe4 23. Qxe4 Rd8 24. Rf7 Qd6 $1 25. Rd7 $140 Rxd7 26. exd7 Qxd7 27. Bb4 Qc8 28. Bxf8 Kxf8 29. Rd6 Qe8 30. Qxe8+ Kxe8 31. Rxc6 Bb7 32. Rc7 Ba6 33. Rc6 $11) 22. O-O-O Bb3 23. Rxf8+ Kxf8 24. Rf1+ Kg8 25. Qc5 dxe4 (25... Qb6 $143 26. Rf7 $1 $36) 26. Rf7 Qd8 27. Qe5 Rh7 28. e7 Qe8 29. Rf8+ Qxf8 30. exf8=Q+ Rxf8 31. Bc3 h5 $11) 20... Bxc4 21. Rf7 Bxd3 22. Rxc7 Bxe4 23. e7 Bxe7 24. Rxe7 Rh7 $11 {[%cal Gg7g5]} *

