 e5 $1 {and the intended d7-d5 break is coming next}) 25... d5 $44) (18. Rc1 d6 19. Qa3 Rb8 20. Be2 O-O 21. Bf3 Bg6 22. Rf1 (22. Bxa7 {can run into} Ra8 $5 (22... Rc8 $44) 23. Bxa8 Qxa8 24. Rg1 e5 $44 {[%csl Rd1]}) 22... Ne4 23. Bxa7 {is risky again in the view of} Rb7 (23... Ra8 $6 24. Qe3) 24. Qe3 (24. Be3 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8a8]} 25. Bxe4 (25. b4 Qh4 $44) 25... Bxe4 26. Qc3 e5 $44) 24... Qa8 25. Bxe4 Bxe4 26. Qxe4 Qxa7 {If Kd1 were not stuck in the center, then the position resembles the Benko Gambit; Black has the characteristic ample compensation. The play may continue with} 27. b3 d5 $1 28. cxd5 (28. Qxe6+ Kh8 29. cxd5 Qxa2 30. Ke1 Rxb3 31. Rf2 Qa5+ 32. Kf1 Rd3 {and the d5-pawn is doomed, with remaining pawns only on the kingside the game should end in a draw}) 28... Qxa2 29. Qc2 (29. Qxe6+ {- 28.Qxe6}) 29... Qa5 30. dxe6 Qd5+ 31. Ke1 Qxe6+ 32. Qe2 Qxe2+ 33. Kxe2 Rxb3 $11) 18... Rc8 $1 ({a developing move and warning for Kd1; instead,} 18... d6 {had assured the castling to the short, but it proved slow after} 19. Qd4 O-O 20. Kc1 $14 {[%cal Gh1d1,Gb2b3] Rd1. In Vachier Lagrave - Praggnanandhaa, Krasnaya Polyana, 2021, White has also been preparing to evacuate the king to a relatively safe square like b2}) (18... d5 $143 19. Bd4 Kf7 20. Rc1 $14 {Rc3, when the king may get to the desired c1-square}) {the greedy} 19. Qxa7 {costs valuable time -} (19. Qa3 d6 20. Ke1 {(back to the dangerous zone)} O-O 21. Rd1 d5 22. Bd4 (22. c5 Bxg2 23. Rg1 Be4 $132) 22... Bxg2 (22... Rf7 23. c5 {Akopian - Radjabov, Heraklion, 2007} Bxg2 24. Rg1 Be4 25. b4 Bg6 $13) 23. Rg1 Be4 24. Qxa7 Bg6 $44) (19. Qd6 Rc6 20. Qa3 d6 21. Ke1 O-O 22. Rd1 a5 $5 (22... Bxg2 23. Rg1 Be4 24. Qxa7 {M. Lukesova- J. Rogos, ICCF email, 2009} Bg6 $44) 23. Rg1 Bg6 $44) (19. Qd4 O-O 20. Rc1 Qa5 21. a3 d6 22. Qxa7 Qf5 23. Bd2 h5 $1 24. Rc3 Rf7 25. Qe3 d5 $44 {[%csl Rd1]}) 19... O-O {and now:} 20. Qd4 (20. Ke1 Ng4 $5 (20... d5 21. Rd1 Qe8 $44) 21. Rd1 (21. Bxg4 $2 Qh4+ 22. g3 Qxg4 23. Rf1 e5 $17) 21... Ra8 22. Qd4 Nxe3 23. Qxe3 d5 $132) (20. a4 d5 $5 $146 {for opening central files is more justified here after the queen's walk to a7, e.g.} (20... Qe7 {has been tested in online chess -} 21. Ra3 (21. Rf1 Bxg2 22. Rg1 Be4 23. Ra3 Rc6 24. Kc1 Rfc8 25. Qd4 Bg6 26. Rxg6 hxg6 27. Kb1 d5 28. c5 Rxc5 {1/2 in R. Williams - M. Reichgeld, ICCF email, 2022, which could see} 29. a5 R5c7 30. a6 Ne4 $11) (21. a5 Rc6 22. Bd2 e5 23. Re1 Qd6 24. Kc1 exf4 25. Qf2 Bd3 $11) 21... Rc6 22. Bd2 Rfc8 23. Qd4 Rd6 24. Qe3 Rb8 25. Rb3 Ra8 26. Re1 (26. Ra3 Rb8 $11) 26... Rxa4 27. Ra3 Rda6 28. c5 Rxa3 29. bxa3 Ra8 $44 {E. Laine - M. Huuskonen, ICCF email, 2022}) 21. Qd4 dxc4 22. Qxd8 Rfxd8+ 23. Ke1 c3 $1 (23... Rb8 24. Bc1 Bxg2 25. Rg1 Bd5 26. a5 $14) 24. bxc3 Rxc3 25. Bb6 (25. Bc1 Nd5 $44) 25... Rd6 26. a5 Rc2 27. Rg1 Nd5 28. Bd1 Rc8 $44) 20... Qe7 $1 ({a useful multifunctional move; it is worth remembering that} 20... d5 $2 {is not timely here because of} 21. c5 $18 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 21. c5 (21. Bf3 Rc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6d6]} 22. Ke2 Bxf3+ 23. gxf3 d6 {Getting ready for a central breakthrough.} 24. Qd3 (24. Kd1 e5) (24. b3 e5 25. fxe5 dxe5 26. Qa7 Qe6 27. Rhg1 Rf7 28. Qa5 e4 $44) 24... e5 25. Kd1 d5 $44 {with typical playing compensation in S. Galanov - T. Ristea, ICCF email, 2019}) (21. b3 d6 22. Re1 Rfd8 23. Rc1 e5 24. Qd2 Qb7 $44) 21... Rfd8 {[%cal Gd7d6]} 22. Qd6 ({an ultimate effort to keep the position closed, for instance,} 22. Rc1 {does not disable} d6 23. cxd6 $140 Rxc1+ 24. Kxc1 Rxd6 25. Qe5 Rc6+ 26. Kd1 h5 $44) 22... Qf7 23. Ke1 ({similar to the last subline is} 23. Qe5 Rc6 24. Ke1 d6 25. cxd6 Rcxd6 26. Rd1 Rxd1+ 27. Bxd1 h5 28. Rf1 Rd5 29. Qb8+ Kh7 30. Rf2 Qg6 $44 {[%cal Gf6g4]}) 23... Bd5 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] A common manoeuvre for leaving the e4-square free for the knight.} 24. Qe5 $5 Ne4 25. Rd1 (25. b4 d6 26. cxd6 Nxd6 $44) (25. Rf1 Nxc5 26. Bxc5 Rxc5 27. Rf2 Rdc8 $44 {J. Ress - H. Corti, LSS email, 2021}) 25... Nxc5 26. f5 Re8 $1 27. fxe6 (27. f6 d6 28. Qg5 Qxf6 29. Qxf6 gxf6 $132) 27... Bxe6 28. Rf1 Bxa2 $1 29. Qxc5 Qb3 30. Qd4 Rxe3 31. Rf3 Rxf3 32. Bxf3 Kh8 $11) (16. g4 $6 {is like playing with fire -} c5 $1 17. Rg1 Ne4 18. Qd3 Qh4 19. Bg2 (19. Rd1 $2 {was refuted by} O-O 20. h3 Rxf4 $19 {Navara - Ris, Ulcinj 2019}) 19... Qxh2 20. Kd1 Nf2+ 21. Bxf2 Bxg2 22. Qe2 Qh3 23. Kd2 Rc8 $15) (16. Rg1 Ne4 17. Qe5 c5 $1 18. Qxg7 Qh4 $1 {A great discovery, all of a sudden Qg7 is in grave danger!} 19. Kd3 (19. Qxh8+ $2 Kf7 20. Qe5 d6 $19 {is the tactical justification of 18....Qh4!}) (19. g3 Qxh2+ 20. Rg2 Qh3 21. Rg1 Qh2+ $11) 19... O-O-O 20. Be2 Qxh2 (20... Rhg8 21. Qe5 Qxh2 {may transpose}) 21. Bf3 Rhg8 22. Qe5 Rg5 $1 23. Rh1 $8 Qg3 24. Rh3 $8 Rxe5 25. Rxg3 Nxg3 26. fxe5 Bxf3 27. gxf3 Rf8 $1 28. f4 h5 29. Rg1 h4 30. Rg2 Kb7 31. Rh2 Kc6 32. Rxh4 {White has avoided material losses and is even a pawn up, but it is not felt after extending the blockade by} Nf5 33. Rh3 a5 $11) (16. b3 Rc8 {[%cal Gc6c5]} ({besides preparing the next step of the c6-pawn, Black can bravely sacrifice it -} 16... c5 $5 17. Qxc5 Ne4 18. Qd4 O-O $44) {, when} 17. c5 {is more a concession than an achievement, as witnessed by} Ba6+ {(solving the problem with the locked Bb7)} 18. Kf3 Bxf1 19. Rhxf1 {and the occupation of the splendid outpost with} Nd5 $11) ({after} 16. Ke1 {Black is facing the same choice -} c5 (16... Rc8 $5 {[%cal Gc6c5] is based on tactical means, for example} 17. c5 Ba6 $1 {[%csl Re1]}) 17. Qxc5 Ne4 18. Qd4 (18. Qh5+ g6 19. Qe5 O-O $132) 18... d6 (18... Qa5+ $5 19. Kd1 d6 {is likely to transpose to the next subline}) 19. Bd3 (19. Qxg7 Qa5+ 20. Kd1 O-O-O 21. Bd3 Nc5 $132) 19... Qa5+ 20. b4 Qxb4+ 21. Kd1 Nc5 22. Rb1 Qa3 23. Bc2 O-O-O $132) 16... Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gc6c5]} (16... c5 $2 17. Qxc5 Rc8 18. Qxa7 $16) 17. g4 ({As before,} 17. c5 {is a strategical concession -} Ba6+ 18. Kf3 Bxf1 19. Rhxf1 Nd5 $11 {[%csl Gd5]}) (17. Bd4 c5 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Kf2 Qc7 $11) (17. Bxa7 $6 c5 18. Bb6 Qe7 19. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $132 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd7d5] Najer - Dreev, Moscow, 2019}) (17. Qc5 {is a better try to hinder 17....c5, but Black can fight for that square with the help of} Qb6 $1 (17... d5 $5 18. g3 Qb6 $13) 18. b4 (18. Qxb6 axb6 19. Bxb6 c5 20. a4 d5 21. a5 Nd7 $11) 18... d5 19. Qxb6 (19. g3 Ne4) ({similar to the featured example is} 19. cxd5 exd5 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Bxb6 O-O 22. Kf3 Ra8 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga8a3]}) 19... axb6 20. Bxb6 Ra8 21. Ra1 Ra4 22. a3 Kf7 $11 {[%cal Gh8a8] with ample compensation in Kadric - Ivic, Germany, 2022}) (17. Rg1 c5 18. g4 {- 17.g4.}) 17... c5 (17... Nxg4 $2 {is a movement in a wrong direction, which is penalized by} 18. Bc5 $18) 18. Rg1 Qc7 $1 {A relatively new trend.} (18... Rc6 19. Qe5 O-O {has been the most popular continuation, but the position after} 20. g5 Nh5 21. Bh3 {is not entirely to my taste.}) 19. g5 (19. Bg2 {has a tactical drawback, which is revealed by the nice shot} Bd5 $1 20. Qxc7 Bxc4+ 21. Kd2 Rxc7 22. Rc1 Bxa2 23. Rxc5 Rxc5 24. Bxc5 Bd5 $11) (19. Ke1 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 h5 $1 21. gxh5 Rxh5 22. Rxg7 Kf8 23. Rg5 Rxh2 24. Rxc5 Bc6 $44 {[%cal Gf6e4] , threatening a fork, while} 25. Rd2 {will be countered with} Rh1 26. Ra5 Ng4 $1) ({Black does not experience any difficulties in case of} 19. f5 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 exf5 21. gxf5 Kf7 22. Bg2 Bxg2 23. Rxg2 Rhe8 24. Kd3 Re5 $11) ({One move later the exchange} 19. Qxc7 Rxc7 {should also not disturb him, for example} 20. Bg2 (20. g5 Ne4 21. Bg2 Ke7 22. Rd3 Rhc8 $11) 20... Ba6 $1 21. b3 Nxg4 22. Bc1 d5 23. f5 Re7 24. Bg5 (24. fxe6 Rxe6+ 25. Kd2 dxc4 26. Bd5 Rd6 $11) 24... Nf6 25. Bxf6 gxf6 26. fxe6 Rxe6+ 27. Kf2 dxc4 (27... d4 $11) 28. Bd5 Re7 $11) 19... Ne4 20. Qe5 (20. Qxc7 Rxc7 {- 19.Qxc7 Rxc7 20.g5}) 20... Kf7 $5 {Questioning the queen for one more time.} (20... d6 $5 {forces} 21. Qxe6+ Kd8 {[%cal Gh8e8] with the clear intention to use the e-file:} 22. g6 (22. Bg2 Re8 23. Qh3 Rb8 $1 24. Bxe4 (24. b3 Nc3+ 25. Kf2 Nxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Qe7 27. Bxb7 Rxb7 28. Qf3 Kc8 29. f5 Qe4 $11) 24... Rxe4 25. f5 (25. g6 h6) 25... Qd7 26. b3 ({here} 26. g6 {can be answered even with} h5 $132) 26... Kc7 $44) 22... Re8 $1 (22... h6 $6 23. Qf7) (22... hxg6 $6 23. Bg2) 23. gxh7 (23. Qf7 hxg6 24. Qxc7+ Rxc7 25. Rxg6 Rce7 $11) 23... Rxe6 24. h8=Q+ Re8 25. Qxg7 Qb6 26. Rg6 (26. Rd3 Rc7 27. Rb3 Qa6 $1 28. Qxc7+ Kxc7 29. Rg7+ Kc6 30. Rbxb7 Qxc4+ 31. Ke1 Qxa2 $1 32. Bb5+ Kd5 33. Bxe8 Qb1+ 34. Ke2 Qc2+ $11) 26... Rc7 {forces White to invest an exchange in order to save the b2-pawn, so} 27. Rgxd6+ $8 Nxd6 28. Qf6+ Kc8 29. Rxd6 Rc6 30. Rxc6+ ({no improvement is} 30. Bh3+ Kb8) 30... Bxc6 31. Kf2 Bd7 $1 32. Qxb6 (32. Qg7 Qe6 33. Qe5 (33. Qg3 Qf6 $11) 33... Qxe5 34. fxe5 Rxe5 $11) 32... axb6 33. h4 Rh8 34. Kg3 Rg8+ $11) 21. Bh3 (21. Qxc7 Rxc7 22. Bg2 h6 $1 {has been tested twice, the online game A. Sorcinelli - G. Bacino, LSS email, 2021, was drawn after} 23. Kd3 ({instead, after} 23. Rdf1 Nd6 {Black created the strong positional threat of planting the knight on f5 after trading the light-squared bishops, in Gadimbayli - Wang Hao, Baku, 2022, White had to show courage and continue anyway with} 24. f5 $1 Nxf5 25. Bh3 hxg5 $140 26. Bxf5 exf5 27. Rxf5+ Kg8 $11) ({the same break can be preceded by} 23. g6+ {as well, e.g.} Ke7 24. f5 exf5 25. Bf4 Rc6 26. Bxe4 fxe4 27. Be5 Re6 28. Bxg7 Rg8 $11) {The play could continue with} 23... d5 24. gxh6 Rxh6 25. f5 Rh4 26. fxe6+ Kxe6 27. cxd5+ Bxd5 $11) 21... g6 22. Rd3 (22. Qxc7 Rxc7 23. Bg2 {is the position from above with a pawn already on g6. Therefore, the ideas with f4-f5 are disabled; Black can go on with} a5 $1 24. Rd3 d5 25. cxd5 (25. Bxe4 dxc4 $1) 25... Bxd5 26. Rc1 Rb7 27. Bxe4 Bxe4 28. Rd2 h6 $1 29. Ke1 hxg5 30. fxg5 Rh3 31. Bxc5 e5 $11) 22... Rhe8 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gd7d5]} 23. Rgd1 d5 24. Ra3 d4 $5 ({The calm reply} 24... a6 {led to a quick transformation to an endgame with opposite-coloured bishops -} 25. Bg2 dxc4 26. Ra4 Qxe5 27. fxe5 Ng3+ 28. hxg3 Bxg2 {After} 29. Rd6 Rb8 30. Bc1 Bd5 31. Rdxa6 Re7 $11 {D. Domanov - B. Ketelhoehn, LSS email, 2021, finished logically in a draw a dozen of moves later.}) 25. Rxa7 Re7 26. Bg2 Qxe5 27. f