1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4 Qc7 9. f4 Qb6 10. c4 Bb4+ 11. Ke2 f5 12. Nf2 Ba6 13. Kf3 Ne7 14. Be3 Bc5 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 16. Qd6 {Trying to establish a blockade on the dark squares.} (16. Qa4 Qb6 $5 ({an alternative is} 16... Bb7 17. h4 Qb6 18. Qa3 c5+ 19. Kg3 h6) 17. c5 {has a drawback of presenting Ne7 with a nice central outpost, the forced} (17. Qa3 c5 18. h4 {is on the verge of transposing to 16....Bb7 from above, but Black also has the typical} Rd8 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gd7d5]} 19. Rd1 $140 d6 20. Rxd6 Rxd6 21. exd6 Qxd6 22. Nd3 Bxc4 {(the mission of Ba6 is fulfilled)} 23. Qxc5 Qd5+ $11) (17. h4 {is aimed at discouraging the thrust g7-g5, but Black has concrete reasons to enter} Qxb2 18. Rd1 ({in reply to} 18. Bd3 {Black is holding due to the clever tactical trick} Bb7 19. Rab1 c5+ 20. Kg3 Bc6 $1 21. Rxb2 Bxa4 22. Be2 Kf7 23. Nd3 Rac8 $11) 18... Bb7 19. Kg3 a5 {and now:} 20. Nd3 (20. Rd3 h6 21. Rb3 Qd2 (21... Qd4 {is about to finish in a repetition as well -} 22. Qa3 Ba6 23. Rd3 Qb6 24. Rb3 Qd4 $11) 22. Rd3 Qb2 $11) 20... Qd4 21. Qa3 g5 $1 {(the standard key to counterplay)} 22. hxg5 Qe3+ 23. Kh2 h6 24. g6 Nxg6 25. Qb2 Ba6 26. Re1 Qa7 27. Qc3 Kf7 {The forced play has ended, Black's chances are not worse -} 28. Be2 h5 $132) 17... Bb5 $1 {makes White choose between different types of endgames -} 18. cxb6 (18. Qxb5 Qxb5 19. Bxb5 cxb5 20. h4 Rc8 21. Rac1 Rc6 22. Rhd1 Nd5 23. h5 Ke7 $11) (18. Bxb5 cxb5 19. cxb6 bxa4 20. bxa7 Rxa7 $11) 18... Bxa4 19. b7 Rb8 20. Nd3 (20. b3 Bb5) 20... c5 $5 ({preferable to} 20... Rxb7 21. Nc5 Rb4 22. a3 Rd4 23. Ke3 Rd1 24. Rxd1 Bxd1 25. Bc4 $1 {and, even though Black will not lose his errant bishop, he will experience problems with his queenside, e.g.} Bc2 26. b4 $44) 21. Nxc5 Bc6+ 22. Kf2 Bxb7 23. Rc1 (23. Nxb7 Rxb7 24. b3 g5 $132) 23... Bc6 24. b3 Kf7 $11) ({The cautious} 16. b3 {is providing Black with the vigorous blow} g5 $1 17. Qd6 g4+ 18. Ke2 Bxc4+ $1 19. bxc4 Qxc4+ 20. Kd1 Qxf4 21. Nd3 Qa4+ 22. Kd2 c5 $1 23. Nxc5 (23. Rc1 Kf7 $132) 23... Qf4+ 24. Kd3 O-O $5 ({if Black is not in his most aggressive mood, then he can choose the restrained} 24... Kf7 {, also with plenty of compensation}) 25. Qxe7 (25. Qd4 Qg5 $44) 25... Rab8 26. Qd6 (26. Be2 Rb4 $1 {must be also enough for a draw at least}) 26... Rb2 $1 27. Rd1 Qf2 $1 28. Nxd7 Qc2+ 29. Ke3 Qf2+ $11) (16. Rc1 $6 g5 $1 $15) 16... Qb6 ({Awful for Black is} 16... Qxd6 $2 17. exd6 Ng8 18. b4 $16) (16... Qa5 {is an option, but a worse one in my opinion because of} 17. h4 Rd8 18. Kg3 c5 19. Rh3 $1 $14 {[%cal Gg3h2] and White is close to a successful regrouping of his forces.}) 17. Be2 $5 {The modern approach - now both rooks can access the d1-square.} (17. b3 {White's usual choice, although this pawn is not hanging in the main text:} Bb7 $5 {My preference goes for this subtle move order:} (17... c5 {The most popular move, albeit not a flexible one, as revealed by} 18. Be2 $5 Bb7+ ({here the thematic} 18... g5 {is well answered with} 19. Nd3 $1) 19. Kg3 Nc8 20. Qd2 d5 21. cxd5 Bxd5 22. h4 Ne7 23. Nd3 O-O 24. Rhc1 Rac8 25. Nb2 Rfd8 26. Qe3 {with more pleasant play for White}) 18. Rd1 (18. Be2 g5 $1 {This strike, which sets the board on fire, makes the difference to the leading text!} 19. fxg5 h6 20. h4 (20. gxh6 c5+ 21. Kf4 Ng6+ 22. Ke3 Rxh6 $132) 20... c5+ 21. Kf4 (21. Kg3 f4+ $1 22. Kg4 Bxg2 23. Qxb6 axb6 24. Rhg1 Bb7 $132) 21... Bxg2 22. Bh5+ Kd8 23. Rhd1 hxg5+ 24. Kxg5 Qb7 $1 25. Rd3 a5 {[%cal Ga8a6]} 26. Rad1 {White seems to prevail, but here comes the stunning} Bd5 27. Nh3 (27. Qxc5 $2 Rxh5+ $1 28. Kxh5 Bf3+) ({if} 27. cxd5 {, then} Qb4 {creates a double threat of mating the king after 28...Rg8 and trapping the queen with 28....Nc8!}) 27... Nc8 28. Qxc5 d6 29. exd6 Qg7+ 30. Kf4 Rxh5 31. Qc7+ Qxc7 32. dxc7+ Kxc7 33. cxd5 Rxh4+ 34. Kg5 Rg4+ 35. Kf6 exd5 36. Rxd5 Ra6+ 37. Kxf5 Rb4 $11) (18. h4 c5+ 19. Kg3 (19. Ke3 Nc8 20. Qxb6 axb6 $11) 19... Qxd6 (19... Nc8 $6 20. Qd2) 20. exd6 Nc8 21. Rd1 a5 {[%cal Ga8a6] will result in an exchange of the c5-pawn for the one on d6 with equality, for example} 22. Be2 (22. Nd3 Nxd6 23. Nxc5 Ke7 24. Rxd6 Kxd6 25. Nxb7+ Kc6 26. Be2 Kxb7 27. Bf3+ Kb6 28. Bxa8 Rxa8 $11) 22... Ra6 23. Nd3 Nxd6 24. Nxc5 Ne4+ 25. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11) 18... c5+ 19. Ke3 (19. Kg3 Qxd6 $1 ({alternatively, the set-up in the leading text} 19... Rd8 20. h4 $140 Nc8 {can be used here as well}) 20. exd6 Ng8 {[%cal Gg8f6]} 21. Nd3 Rc8 22. Be2 {S. Fedorchuk - M. Petrov, Tournefeuille, 2009} Nf6 23. Kf2 (23. Bf3 Bxf3 24. gxf3 Rc6 $11) 23... a5 {and, even though White can plant his knight on the perfect e5-square, his edge is more of symbolic character -} 24. Ne5 O-O {or 24...Ra8 at once.}) 19... Kf7 $5 ({compared to the abovementioned game Fedorchuk - Petrov, here} 19... Qxd6 $6 {is ill-timed, after} 20. exd6 {Black cannot rely on 20....Nc8 because of 21.Nd3! and he is therefore limited to} Ng8 21. Nd3 Rc8 22. Be2 Nf6 23. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gh1g1,Gg2g4] with a better version (Ke3 instead of on g3 in particular) for his opponent}) ({here too, Black can consider} 19... Rd8 {[%cal Ge7c8]} 20. Be2 Nc8 21. Qxb6 axb6 22. a4 d6 23. exd6 Nxd6 {and eventual trade of the bishops will enable Black to transfer his knight to one of the a5- or c6-squares}) 20. Qxb6 (20. Be2 Rhd8 21. Nd3 Rac8 $11) 20... axb6 21. Rxd7 Bc6 22. Rd2 g5 $1 {The thematic blow:} 23. Nh3 (23. fxg5 h6 ({similar is} 23... Ng6 24. Nd3 h6 $132) 24. gxh6 Rxh6 25. Nd3 Ng6 26. h4 Rah8 27. Nf4 Nxe5 28. Be2 {(returning the other extra pawn for own activity)} Rxh4 29. Rxh4 Rxh4 30. Rd6 Rh6 31. Bf3 {A critical moment - it seems that White is breaking through on the queenside, but here comes} Ke7 $1 32. Rxc6 Nxc6 33. Bxc6 Rh1 $11 {and suddenly the b6-pawn is in safety, while the active rook guarantees enough counterchances, so the opponents in R. Cvak - D. Cleto, LSS email, 2020, have quickly come to a peaceful end.}) 23... gxf4+ 24. Nxf4 Rhd8 $1 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Be2 (26. Bd3 {will be answered with the same} Ng6 {with rich play against the e5- and g2-pawns}) 26... Ng6 27. Nxg6 (27. Bh5 Rd4) 27... hxg6 28. Bf3 ({Black is holding in the bishop ending} 28. Rd1 Rxd1 29. Bxd1 Bxg2 30. h4 Kg7 31. Kf4 Kh6 32. Be2 Be4 33. a3 Bc2 34. b4 Bb3 $11) 28... Bxf3 29. gxf3 g5 30. h4 {So far Albornoz Cabrera - Sandoval Mercado, Merida, 2022, when Black seems to have enough counterplay after} f4+ (30... Rh8 31. h5 Kg7 $11) 31. Ke2 Rh8 32. h5 Kg7 33. a4 Kh6 34. Rd1 Re8 35. Rd6 Kxh5 36. Rxb6 g4 37. fxg4+ Kxg4 $11 {[%csl Gf4,Gg4]}) (17. Rd1 {appears to be a bit premature in the view of a pure materialistic operation like} Qxb2 $1 18. Nd3 (18. Qxd7+ Kf7 19. Qd2 Rhb8 $11) 18... Qxa2 $1 19. Nc5 (19. Nb4 Qa3+ 20. Rd3 Qa4 21. Nxa6 Qxa6 22. Qxd7+ Kf7 23. Rd6 Qc8 $11) 19... Bxc4 20. Bxc4 Qxc4 21. Rd4 Qa2 22. Qxd7+ ({the game can already end in a repetition after} 22. Rd2 Qc4 $11 {, for the queen should protect the e6-pawn}) 22... Kf7 23. Nb7 Rhb8 24. Rd3 $1 Kf8 (24... Rxb7 25. Qxb7 Qc4 26. Rhd1 $140 Qe4+ 27. Kf2 Qxf4+ 28. Kg1 Re8 $11 {seems reliable, but Black is by no means forced to extreme measures}) 25. Nc5 Kf7 26. Nb7 $11) (17. h4 {is providing Black with time for the similar capture} Qxb2 18. Bd3 $140 Qb6 19. Rab1 Qa5 20. Rhc1 Nc8 21. Qb4 Qxb4 22. Rxb4 c5 23. Rb3 d6 $11) ({Finally,} 17. b4 {does not disable the intended} c5 $1 18. Rd1 $140 (18. bxc5 Qb2 $132) 18... Bb7+ 19. Kg3 cxb4 20. Qxd7+ Kf7 21. c5 Qc6 22. Qxc6 Bxc6 23. Rd6 Rhb8 $132) 17... Rd8 $1 {[%cal Ge7c8] The best - Black keeps all his options open, here they are in brief:} (17... Qxb2 $2 18. Nd3 Qb8 19. Nc5 $16) (17... g5 {is possible, but White's prospects are objectively higher after} 18. fxg5 Ng6 19. h4 Qb8 20. Qxb8+ Rxb8 21. b3 Nxe5+ 22. Kf4 $1 ({a clear improvement over} 22. Ke3 {in Kaczur - Cheparinov, Porec 2022, when I could continue with} c5 $1 23. g4 O-O $11) 22... d6 (22... Ng6+ 23. Ke3) 23. g4 Ng6+ 24. Kg3 f4+ 25. Kh3 $14) (17... c5 $6 18. Rhd1 Rd8 19. Ke3 $14) 18. b4 {A big effort to keep the key c5-square under control compared to:} (18. Rad1 c5 ({still risky is} 18... Qxb2 $6 19. Rc1 $36) ({White is able to exert pressure after} 18... Nc8 19. Qa3 $1 c5 20. Rd2 O-O 21. Rhd1 $14 {as well}) 19. Ke3 ({after} 19. b3 Nc8 {is coming at the right moment}) 19... Nc8 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. b3 Bb7 22. a4 d6 {Black has prepared everything for this liberating push -} 23. Nd3 Be4 24. exd6 Bxd3 25. Rxd3 Nxd6 26. a5 bxa5 27. Ra1 Ke7 28. Rxa5 Ne4 29. g4 Ra8 30. Rb5 Rhb8 $11) ({here} 18. Rhd1 $6 {is a signal for} g5 $1 19. fxg5 h6 20. gxh6 Ng6 21. g3 Rxh6 $132) (18. Rac1 c5 19. Ke3 Bb7 20. b3 Nc8 21. Qxb6 axb6 $11 {[%cal Gd7d6]}) (18. Rab1 c5 19. b3 Bb7+ 20. Kg3 Nc8 ({going for the standard d7-d6 break, but} 20... Rg8 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 21. h4 h6 {deserves attention -} 22. Nd3 Rc8 $11) 21. Qxb6 axb6 22. b4 d6 23. Rhd1 cxb4 24. exd6 Rxd6 25. Rxd6 Nxd6 26. Rxb4 Ke7 27. Rxb6 Rc8 $11) 18... Nc8 $1 19. Qc5 {The only way to keep the grip on the dark squares.} (19. Qd2 $6 c5 20. b5 Bb7+ 21. Kg3 d5 22. Rhd1 O-O $132) 19... d5 $1 {Black has to play energetically in order to free himself, now his counterplay is concentrated against the c4-pawn and along the a6-f1 diagonal respectively.} (19... d6 $143 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Rhd1 $14) 20. exd6 ({Black has nothing to complain after} 20. cxd5 Qxc5 21. bxc5 Bxe2+ 22. Kxe2 Rxd5 $11) ({So is with} 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. c5 (21. b5 Bb7 22. c5 Na4 $11) 21... Bxe2+ 22. Kxe2 Nc4 23. a4 (23. h4 a5) 23... g5 24. fxg5 Nxe5 25. b5 Kd7 $132) 20... Nxd6 21. Qe5 {The most principled continuation compared to:} (21. Rhc1 $5 Qxc5 22. bxc5 Nf7 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 23. Rc3 {[%cal Gc3a3]} (23. Nd3 g5 $1 24. fxg5 (24. g3 Ke7) 24... Nxg5+ 25. Ke3 O-O 26. h4 Nf7 27. Bf3 e5 28. Nb4 (28. Bxc6 f4+ 29. Ke2 Rd4 $132) 28... e4 $1 29. Be2 Bb7 30. Rf1 Ne5 31. Rad1 Rde8 $11) 23... e5 $1 24. Ra3 Bc8 25. Rxa7 g5 $1 26. g3 (26. fxg5 Nxg5+ 27. Kg3 Rd7 28. Rxd7 Kxd7 $44) 26... O-O 27. Rd1 Rde8 28. fxg5 Nxg5+ 29. Kg2 e4 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 30. h4 f4 $1 31. hxg5 (31. gxf4 Ne6 $11) 31... f3+ 32. Bxf3 exf3+ 33. Kf1 Re5 $11) (21. Qxb6 axb6 22. Rhc1 (22. c5 Bxe2+ 23. Kxe2 bxc5 24. bxc5 Nb5 $11) 22... c5 23. bxc5 bxc5 24. Nd3 Rc8 25. Ne5 Nf7 $11) 21... c5 $1 22. Qxg7 {Consequent and probably the best, even though White, given the insecure location of Kf3, is taking certain risks on himself by opening the g-file.} ({Harmless is} 22. Qxc5 Qxc5 ({much simpler than} 22... Rc8 23. Qxb6 axb6 24. Rhc1 Bxc4 25. Bxc4 Nxc4 26. Nd3 Ke7 27. a4 Rhd8 28. Ke2 Rd4 $11 {Firouzja - Rapport, Bucharest, 2022}) 23. bxc5 Nb7 24. c6 Na5 $11) (22. Rhd1 Nxc4 ({there is no particular reason Black to avoid simplifications, but he can also preserve the queens, for instance} 22... O-O $5 23. Qxc5 Qb8 $1 24. Qe5 Qb7+ 25. Kg3 Nf7 $44) 23. Rxd8+ Kxd8 24. Bxc4 (24. Rd1+ Kc8) 24... Bxc4 25. bxc5 Qc7 $11) (22. bxc5 $2 Qc6+ 23. Kg3 Nf7 24. Qe3 g5 $17) 22... Nf7 {Striving at a complicated fight.} ({The calmer} 22... Rf8 $5 23. Kg3 {and only now} Nf7 {seems fully playable -} 24. Bh5 Ke7 25. Bxf7 Rxf7 26. Qg5+ Kf8 $13) 23. b5 Bb7+ 24. Ke3 (24. Kg3 $2 Ke7 $19 {[%cal Gd8g8,Gh8g8]}) 24... e5 $1 {Black's point, he is trying to get to the wandering king.} 25. Bh5 (25. Nh3 {is running into} Qg6 $1 26. Qxg6 hxg6 {, after} 27. Kf2 {Black can liquidate to a favourable ending by} Rxh3 28. gxh3 Bxh1 29. Rxh1 exf4 30. Rd1 Rxd1 31. Bxd1 Ne5 $11) 25... exf4+ 26. Ke2 (26. Kxf4 $2 Qc7+ $19) 26... Qe6+ 27. Kf1 Qxc4+ (27... Rf8 $5 {at once is a decent option again, e.g.} 28. Re1 Be4 29. h4 Ke7 $13) 28. Kg1 Rf8 29. h3 (29. Re1+ $2 Kd7 $17) (29. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh1h3]} Kd7 $1 {It is necessary to leave the dangerous central zone:} 30. Rh3 {is the logical follow-up of the previous move, Black has sufficient counterplay after evacuating his king to the queenside at first -} ({analogous to the main line is} 30. Rd1+ Kc8 31. Rxd8+ Rxd8 32. Bxf7 (32. Qxf7 Qc1+ 33. Kh2 Qe3 34. Qxf5+ Kc7 35. Rg1 Qg3+ 36. Kh1 Qxf2 37. Qe5+ $11) 32... Qe2 $1 33. Rh3 Rd2 (33... Qe1+ $5 34. Kh2 f3) 34. Qf8+ Kd7 35. Be8+ Qxe8 36. Qxf5+ Qe6 37. Rd3+ Rxd3 38. Qxh7+ Kc8 39. Nxd3 Qe3+ 40. Kf1 Be4 $11) 30... Kc7 $1 31. Re1 Rg8 $5 32. Qxf7+ Qxf7 33. Bxf7 Rxg2+ 34. Kf1 Rd7 (34... Rg3 $5 35. Rh2 Rd2 $44) 35. Bc4 f3 {[%cal Gd7g7]} 36. Re3 (36. Nd3 Rdg7) 36... Rd4 $132) 29... Kd7 $1 30. Rd1+ Kc8 31. Rxd8+ Rxd8 32. Qxf7 ({In case of} 32. Bxf7 Qe2 $1 {is arresting the knight -} 33. Qg5 Qe3 $11 34. Kh2 $140 Rf8 $1) 32... Qc1+ 33. Kh2 Qe3 34. Qxf5+ Kc7 35. Rg1 (35. Qxh7+ Rd7 36. Qg6 Qxf2 $11) 35... Qxf2 36. a4 (36. Qe5+ Kb6 37. Qf6+ Kc7 $11) 36... Qg3+ 37. Kh1 Rd5 38. Qxh7+ Rd7 39. Qf5 Rd5 40. Qe4 (40. Qh7+ Rd7 $11) 40... Qe3 $1 {A surprising point - by trading the queens Black is solving the problem with his exposed king and the passed c-pawn will gain in importance.} 41. Qxe3 (41. Qg6 Rd6 42. Qf7+ Rd7 $11) ({Another balanced rook ending arises after} 41. Bf3 Qxe4 42. Bxe4 Rd4 43. Bxb7 Kxb7 $11 44. a5 $140 a6 45. b6 Ra4 46. Rf1 Rxa5 47. Rxf4 Rb5 48. g4 a5 $1 49. Rc4 Rxb6 50. g5 Ra6 51. Rxc5 (51. Ra4 $144 c4 52. Rxc4 a4) 51... a4 52. Rc2 a3 53. Ra2 Kc7 $11) 41... fxe3 42. Bf3 Rd2 43. Bxb7 Kxb7 44. Re1 e2 45. Kg1 c4 {White's hopes are connected with his kingside pawns, but he must keep the balance - with correct play the position is a draw by force.} 46. Kf2 c3 47. Ke3 Rb2 48. Rc1 $8 Rc2 (48... e1=Q+ 49. Rxe1 Rxg2 $11) ({even more forcing is} 48... Rd2 49. Re1 $8 Rb2 $8 50. Rc1 $8 $11) 49. Re1 Rb2 $11 *

